WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm Emilye Crosby, we have the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
and I'm conducting this oral history as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:26.000
which is being undertaken by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
and the American Folklife Center of the Library of Congress.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:40.000
And John Bishop is here with us today and we're interviewing Lisa Anderson Todd and its June 24th, 2014.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
2013.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:43.000
2013.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Yes.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
June 24th, 2013 at Ms. Todd's home in Washington, DC.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Thanks very much for doing the interview with us today.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Can you tell me a little bit about your family and your early background growing up?

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
I'm the daughter of Corporate Lawyer, my father, Carl Anderson.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And my mother was a psychiatric social worker.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:19.000
They came from the Midwest after my father got his law degree to New York City.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And I grew up in Summit, New Jersey when my father got a corporate job in New Jersey.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:47.000
And I have two older brothers.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:55.000
It was typical 1950s suburban living.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
My mother never worked.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
She worked one year when I was in eighth grade.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Went back to work, but she decided after one year that she couldn't do it all.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
She had her full responsibilities at home.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
My father didn't participate.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:24.000
They were interested in public service.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
I have that example.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
But they were not particularly liberal.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
My father was a Republican.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:41.000
He was afraid of signing documents because of the McCarthy scare.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
He remembered that.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
He had a lot of things to do with the mayor.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.000
He grew up poor, one of six children in Hibbing, Minnesota.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:10.000
And I think that influence, terror, and influence me in having an interest in the poor and the excluded the downtrodden.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:19.000
I did not have exposure to local blacks.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:32.000
There were blacks in my junior high school, but they were not my friends.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So your mother is from Hibbing, Minnesota?

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Hibbing is got an interesting history, doesn't it?

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:48.000
I think that part of Minnesota had some strong organizing and as well as the poverty convention.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
My understanding was that it was very ethnic community.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
The Slavs didn't talk to the Finns.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
But it was a very wealthy community.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:13.000
the Iron Ore Mines, made facilities available to Hibbing High School today, is a model with a swimming pool.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
And my mother benefited from that educational experience.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
She went to Hibbing, junior college, and then transferred to the University of Minnesota.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So that's interesting.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
I knew that the Iron Range, but I wouldn't necessarily have thought that would translate into the public facilities for everybody.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Yes, yes.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So when did you first become more aware of racial issues or interested in social justice kinds of issues?

00:04:49.000 --> 00:05:12.000
I was influenced to do the kind of work that began me on that journey to Freedom Summer by spending a summer in Northern Sweden on the The Experiment in International Living.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And I lived in a remote area with a family for one month, traveled with a group of 10 kids.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And at the end of that summer, I said, what do I want to do next summer?

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
I'd love to go back to Europe. I was following the example of my older brother.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And he had gone on an American Friends Service Committee work project in Italy and helped build a school.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And I said to myself, I don't want a vacation because that's what my experiment summer was like.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Next summer, I want to do something.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And I said to myself that there are plenty of problems in the United States.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
I don't want to go back to Europe.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And I researched work camps.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:25.000
And I was very fortunate to be able to sign up for two work camps, the summer of 1963.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:40.000
I participated in a project of the Ecumenical Voluntary Service at Tougaloo College.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:49.000
We did maintenance work for the college that had not been done before.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And in the course of doing that, we were learning about the Civil Rights Movement.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:01.000
We went to nonviolent training workshops.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
We heard speakers in the Social Science Lab.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And we had an incredible day on August 1, 1963, going up to Greenwood to the SNCC office at the invitation of Bob Moses.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And going to a mass meeting that evening, we split up our group of ten.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So I guess there were three or four of us that went to Ruleville and had dinner at Fannie Lou Hamer's home.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:48.000
And she told the story to us of the beating in Winona.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:58.000
And I can remember her saying, or I wrote in my diary that she said, I didn't know that Fannie Lou Hamer.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And going to the mass meeting that evening was an incredible experience for me.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:10.000
We had been to mass meetings in Jackson, but that was so different.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:15.000
You described it.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:37.000
The reception that we got from mostly women, the welcome, the sense that, and the feeling that you had that these people were risking so much to want to register to vote when the sanctions were so severe.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:54.000
And the risk of the nightrider shooting in their homes, the loss of a job, the loss of credit that they needed to run their form or whatever.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
And there they were saying to us, we appreciate your being here.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And your interest in us in a situation where I understand they did not know friendly white people.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And we were friendly white people.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:18.000
So we were accorded a special attention.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.000
And we sang, we shall overcome.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Arm over arm, holding hands. And it was emotional for me.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And then I said, what am I going to do?

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
These people will expect that I go back home and forget.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And I didn't want to forget because it meant a lot to me.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:50.000
A number of the kids in the group, we took off for New Orleans, had a little weekend.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And one of the women on the project was going on to Greensboro, North Carolina with me.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:08.000
We just happened to be, had signed up for a second American Friend Service Committee project.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:15.000
And we, there were 18 of us, we lived in the basement of a church.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And we were there for voter registration.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:31.000
We only worked from, I think, five PM to nine PM, House to House Cambossing.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
The registrars were cooperative.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:39.000
They were right in the neighborhood, ready to take the person's application.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
There had been demonstrations in the spring.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
People were very receptive to going to register to vote.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And we were able to register 803 people, mostly Democrats, but some Republicans.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And what I gained from that experience was an understanding of,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:12.000
my black peers, because we had a group of one guy, local guy, Pat Patterson.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And the girls from Greensboro, Randall and John's and Elfria artists and Bunky Dan Speed,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
we had a lot of fun.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:28.000
And Karen paid the, the, the, the Galfre Morgan that I traveled with from Mississippi.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
It was such a contrast to Mississippi.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And it made me comfortable in the black community.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
How was it a contrast with Mississippi?

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
We were special in Mississippi.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.000
We were white.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:55.000
When I went to a mass meeting in Jackson, our group, I don't know whether it was the whole group of ten students or fewer of us.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:01.000
Spottswood W. Robinson III, the head of the NAACP, was speaking.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:08.000
They sat us on the stage.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
You know, we were the only whites in the crowd.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:22.000
And there was a fear of traveling and being white in the black community in Mississippi.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
In 1963, we were being careful.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And in Greensboro, there was much more freedom.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:43.000
The other thing that, that I was fortunate to do in Greensboro was go to parties and learn about black men.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:56.000
And we, the parties started at 11 o'clock and we had this, our little group of friends.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And we got to talk about when we went back to the church.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
We're all living in the same basement of the church.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.000
And it was no big deal.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So the summer of 64, that was not a big deal for me.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:18.000
I had kind of done that. I had explored relations with black men.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And I knew that it's just like relations with white men.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
So it's no big deal.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Although historically, it is.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
Maybe between individual people, but in the larger context.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
It's a maybe between individual people.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:40.000
It means one thing. And in the larger context, it has a different kind of meeting.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:47.000
So back in Esquil, a little bit more about in Mississippi, you talked about doing the workshops on nonviolence.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And you're out at Tougaloo and going to the Massouds.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Can you talk about what the workshop is?

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Can we hold up a second?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
So can you tell me about the nonviolence workshops in Mississippi and then also who the people,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.000
are there people that you remember meeting at Tougaloo and in the while you were in Mississippi?

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Can you tell me about that?

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:22.000
I think Corps was largely doing the work in Jackson in 1963.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
I met Dave Dennis there.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:34.000
I remember asking him, I remember because I kept a detailed diary that summer.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:43.000
Asking him why were children used in the Birmingham demonstrations?

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Because that was controversial at the time.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:53.000
The spring of 1963 when the hoses and the dogs were out to stop the demonstrators.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:03.000
And he said, we want children to learn about how to stand up for freedom.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.000
Before they learn other things from their parents.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:12.000
That's interesting.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Memphis Norman, was heading the social science lab that summer.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:23.000
I regretted that I did not meet Dr. (Ernst) Borinski.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
He was apparently on vacation.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:31.000
I did not meet John Salter Jr Jr, who was not on campus at all.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
But we spent a lot of time with Rev. Rev. Ed King.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And I looked at his scarred face and thought that that was related to the tremendous sacrifice he was making to be a part of the Civil Rights Movement as a white southerner from the expert.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:00.000
So you must have been there shortly after my grievers was assassinated?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Yes. I read that story in the New York Times before I left home.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And interesting story.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
Getting on the plane to fly to Jackson by myself.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Not being a frequent flyer.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I looked out my window and the engine was on fire.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:36.000
And I didn't know what that meant because I had not been doing a lot of flying.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:45.000
But we landed not at nearby Teterboro, New Jersey, which would have been a problem, but went back to New York.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
And my parents were still there.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
And that was a moment of truth.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Wouldn't it be easier to stay home?

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:08.000
But we got on another slow flight and I had a lot of time to think about what I was getting into.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But I went ahead and it was so instructive.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:23.000
We had two black students in the group, Ivory Phillips, who has become an educator in Jackson.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
I've seen him recently.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And Thelma Sadbury, who I understand lives in Detroit, but I have not been able to connect with her.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:41.000
We had speakers that came to us in the evening.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Timothy Jenkins spoke to us about the status of the civil-pending civil rights bill.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Jane Schutt, a remarkable white woman from Jackson, Mississippi, was so impressive the work that she was doing.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:07.000
Through the church, through the interracial prayer groups and on the advisory council.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:18.000
We had an evening at Dr. (Daniel) Beittel's home.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:27.000
Allan Knight Chalmers, I think it is, from New York, spoke to us.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:42.000
He was very pessimistic about when Jackson was going to change and become less of a segregated city.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Because they did not have a corporate structure that would influence them from outside as Birmingham had.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Do you remember the actual dates that you were in Jackson that summer?

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:13.000
I think it was July 6th to August 3rd.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:18.000
So the big demonstrations were pretty much over and done with by then.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:31.000
The federal government had influenced Jackson to stop demonstrating, to stop direct action protests, to move into voter registration.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:42.000
As I understand it, there would be a way that foundation money could support SNCC's voter registration work.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:46.000
That would be less confrontational with the local government.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:20:08.000
In addition, the NAACP decided to stop providing bail for all the demonstrators who were so quickly arrested and so mistreated in jail that they needed to get out.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:19.000
Charles Evers had come in to take over the NAACP and they were beginning demonstrations again.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.000
But on a small scale and not wanting to be arrested.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:32.000
And in the nonviolent workshops where core people were trying to recruit, they were not getting very good participation.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:45.000
And the explanation possibly is that the students had been so mistreated in jail that they were not ready to go back and demonstrate again.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Knowing that they were not going to be getting out quickly, the bail had been doubled in the amount.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:16.000
You said you kept a detailed diary. So do you remember, do you know from your diary, whether what kind of conversations were going on in the community or among activists about the national NAACP's decisions and these issues of what was going on in the aftermath of the assassination and all that?

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:21.000
I didn't have much contact with local people.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:44.000
I remember or I have read in my diary about Dr. Bitals position that people were critical of the NAACP coming in as outsiders, distinguishing their approach from that of core and SNCC.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Which came in and lived in the community and stayed in the community and became a part of the community and took the same risks that the community was taking and that that was more effective strategy to encourage local people to register and participate.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:23.000
And it's interesting because of course in my understanding is that the North Jackson youth branch of the NAACP which was working with John Salter Jr Jr and Megarevres and Rev. Rev. Ed King was really crucial so that there's a real split between the local NAACP, especially the youth and the national organization.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And so I don't know if you heard anything about that at the time.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:37.000
Well, I think you're absolutely correct.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:44.000
That would be my understanding also.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:53.000
I think the position of Johnny Frazier is interesting there. I have seen him since and he came out of Greenville.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Yeah, what does he say about it?

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Well, I don't know what he said at the time.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:23.000
My favorite statement from Johnny Frazier is that when he said to me, thank you for coming.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:28.000
But we're getting ahead of ourselves.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:42.000
So you had these two experiences with Tougulu. Well, actually, what was Bob Moses like? How did you meet him? Did he come and talk to the group or did the invitation come?

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:47.000
How did the invitation come to go to Greenwood?

00:23:47.000 --> 00:24:00.000
He was on campus one day and we were anxious. We heard about SNCC, one of the first days.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:13.000
But I'm not sure who it was now that that was on campus or that was on campus.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:21.000
And Bob Moses did not want to speak to our group because he had to leave.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:27.000
There was a dance that evening at the Student Center. Bob Moses was at the dance.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:34.000
And I was very annoyed that he wouldn't talk to us.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:45.000
But it was natural for him to invite us to see the SNCC headquarters.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:52.000
That was where all the work was being done out of Greenwood at that time.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:56.000
So do you remember? What was Mrs. Hamer like?

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:04.000
She said that she told you that story and she must have been a pretty recent event at that point.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:15.000
She stood in the doorway. She cooked us dinner. We're sitting outside at her home.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:27.000
And we invited her to sit down and eat with us. And she said that the first time she ate with an integrated group was at Tougaloo.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:36.000
I mean that she had done that. I think she registered to vote in 1962 in the spring.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:47.000
I described her as a short, fat woman with her hair sticking straight out or something when she greeted us.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:57.000
Who is this? I had no idea who Fannie Lou Hamer was.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:02.000
So what was it like? So you have no idea and then you meet her.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
What was that?

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:12.000
The way she spoke is absolutely captivating.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:21.000
She talked about her water bill had increased so much.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:32.000
And I think she mentioned that her home had been shot into when she was sleeping somewhere else.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:38.000
I had a sense right away of how powerful she was, how courageous she was.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:49.000
She understood the attitude of white people. I think it's my anecdote from my diary that,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:56.000
or else I've read it in a book that if you had a shade tree, you wouldn't want to just give it up, would you?

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:03.000
Nope.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:11.000
Kind of gets right to the heart of things, doesn't it, when you're in Delta Mississippi? Right, right.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:15.000
Were there other people that you met in Ruleville or Greenwood that you remember?

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:22.000
No, no. You mentioned that it the church, it was mostly women?

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Yes. You just walk around the corner to the Williams Chapel Church where all their mass meetings were, I think.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:38.000
And there was a reverend there.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:45.000
I guess Charles McLaurin was speaking.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:52.000
There were some SNCC guys that went over from Greenwood to Ruleville.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:28:00.000
And I felt comforted by that because they would know what to do where we were going.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:07.000
So after that summer and you have these two different very important experiences,

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:10.000
you're in school at Cornell at the time? Yes.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:17.000
And we haven't talked at all about what your college experience was like other than these programs off campus.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:22.000
So what were you involved in at Cornell and doing at Cornell?

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:34.000
Cornell was a difficult adjustment for me because I had been at an All Girls Independent Day School in summit for four years.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:43.000
And here I was thrown into this huge university by myself.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:57.000
And I did not find the people I expected in my immediate living surroundings in the dormitory.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:01.000
My first semester and I was I was unhappy.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Second semester I pledged a sorority and found a group of very interesting women, diverse women.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:22.000
Our sorority was pledging Jewish girls at a time when the national did not expect that to be the case.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:36.000
And it turned out after I left that as a result of that Kappa Alpha Theta Cornell lost its charter and went local with the support of the Cornell administration.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:30:05.000
But because of rushing Jewish girls and avoiding the requirements of getting two references, one from any Theta alum and one from the alum from the girls hometown, they stopped rushing the year after I left.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:12.000
So was it those kind of attitudes that drew you to that group do you think?

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:17.000
Were those the kinds of attitudes that drew you to that group in the first place?

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:21.000
Yes, yes, the diversity.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:30.000
And well, just some crazy individuals. It was a lot of fun.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:38.000
And challenging academically, I mean I was always an overachieving student.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:46.000
I did well in school by working hard, not by native intelligence.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:31:02.000
I did not. I was extracurricular in high school but I quickly got that out of my system at college.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:18.000
I was studying and joined this authority dating. I wanted to work my junior year.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:28.000
My father didn't want me to work. I thought that I would be taking a job away from a student who needed to work and didn't want to disclose his finances.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:40.000
I'm sure the university also. But somehow we got around that and I had a job in the library for one semester.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:50.000
I was not demonstrating. I took a race-race relations sociology course my junior year.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.000
My major was American Studies government.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:00.000
Was that a course that you picked or was it something that was part of the program?

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:08.000
I elected that course. Robin M. Williams Jr was a noted sociology professor at Cornell.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:12.000
Was the class useful to you? I think so.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
For basic information.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:20.000
You took that then before you did the two summer projects.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:26.000
Yes.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:31.000
Do you think that might have influenced you to pick out those two work projects?

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:40.000
I did. There weren't many options for those summer work camps in the United States.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:47.000
I did choose Tougaloo, Mississippi, over Brownsville, Texas.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:57.000
I did turn down an option to be a paid dietician on a project for the American Friends Service Committee.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:01.000
What was it that drew you to Tougaloo over Brownsville?

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:10.000
It was the civil rights situation that was in the news and in my consciousness.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.000
But not as an activist.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:17.000
The summer of 63 I felt also. I was not an activist.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.000
I was learning about the movement. It was very easy.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.000
I talked in my diary about making a commitment.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
That's what we talked about then. Which side are you on?

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:34.000
It was very controversial throughout the country.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:39.000
How did your parents feel about you going to Mississippi and Greensboro?

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:45.000
They supported me.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:49.000
There wasn't any question that I could do that.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:55.000
I think it was my own money that I had saved.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:05.000
I worked in a department store after my freshman year in college in Newark.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:12.000
Even though their politics were not necessarily leaning that way,

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:18.000
your father was concerned about the red scare stuff.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.000
He wasn't worried about you going south.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:34.000
The other part that's interesting about my father is that he was asked to be the corporate giving chairman for the United Negro College Fund.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:41.000
As a result of his work at his company with a company foundation.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:50.000
He was meeting HBCU presidents at these meetings.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:54.000
At one dinner he sat next to Lorraine Hansberry.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:00.000
He asked her what she did.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:06.000
Oops.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:12.000
In addition to that, he was active in the Lutheran Church of America.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:24.000
I think he had some reason there in the church for him to support me.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:30.000
Although he was not at all vocal in his religion.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:37.000
He went to church after he got the three kids through Sunday school and confirmed.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:43.000
My uncle was active in the church in St. Paul.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:47.000
I think recommended that he participate in the national church.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:55.000
He was elected treasurer of the Lutheran Church of America.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:01.000
So after you did that summer 63 and you're back on campus, does that change things?

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:04.000
Yes.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:10.000
I became active with the Cornell United religious work.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Paul Gibbons, who was the United Church of Christ representative at CURW.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:29.000
He was an organized group interested in civil rights.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:35.000
Our project was to work for passage of the Civil Rights Act.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:45.000
I went to some conferences and we put out a newsletter.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:48.000
I saw the newsletter recently.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
Did you remember that?

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:54.000
I did.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:07.000
I did have something that I wanted to do going back to college after the summer experiences in Mississippi and North Carolina.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:20.000
My roommate told me recently that I was back at Cornell my senior year, a different person.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
Did she say how?

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:27.000
No, I asked her. What do you mean?

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
She never answered.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:37.000
She was often China, you know, as a professor of political science.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:44.000
So did you have, were you connected with any friends of SNCC or any of those kinds of support work?

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:49.000
Or was it primarily the religious base group in the lobbying?

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:52.000
I met Jane Stembridge at Tougaloo.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:38:02.000
She was there working on the literacy books that they were planning to use,

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.000
a major literacy project in Mississippi.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:13.000
And I was very impressed with her, of course, wanted to spend more time with her than we had to spend and talk.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:21.000
But she contacted SNCC in Atlanta and made sure that everyone in our group received the SNCC literature.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And obviously we were supposed to go back to our college campuses and start a friends of SNCC chapter that would raise money for SNCC work in the South.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:33.000
I didn't do that.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:38.000
Can you tell me what Jane was like when you met her there?

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:45.000
Interesting.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:52.000
A sensitive woman, as I say, I wanted to spend more time with her.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:57.000
I think I received one letter from her later.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:14.000
What I remember, what I wrote down, what I recall is that she said that Bob Moses was a saint.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:23.000
They had a good summer together in summer of 1960.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:27.000
So she was in Tougaloo by that summer.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:32.000
I'm just trying to think of the timing of that.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
Was she writing poetry then?

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:38.000
Not that I knew of.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:44.000
I've found her book. I've gotten her book. I haven't read it yet.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:51.000
So what do you remember much about the lobbying on the Civil Rights Act and how you did that?

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:57.000
We took a trip to Washington Spring vacation and sat in the chamber.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:03.000
I think we heard the debate on the Senate floor.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:08.000
We were supposed to visit individual congressmen. I don't remember that part.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:12.000
We stayed with some people in Bethesda.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:19.000
And what I remember is the way that man drove Rock Creek Parkway.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
That was that.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Very skillfully, very fast.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:30.000
In the morning at Russia, it's four lanes in one direction.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:33.000
And it's a winding road.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:36.000
And it's a long way from Bethesda.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:38.000
It's all the way to Capitol Hill.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:42.000
Race car driver.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:46.000
At what point did you hear about Freedom Summer?

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:54.000
I applied to Work for Snick in the fall of 63.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:41:00.000
And I got a letter from Walter Tillow that said,

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:11.000
Snick is planning a project that will include Freedom Schools and legal resources and voter registration.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:18.000
And you should contact the Jackson office, I think.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:24.000
So I was an early applicant.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:39.000
And I got these notes on the letter as back that we might be able to find a way to pay you,

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.000
which I thought was strange.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:47.000
But I quickly was in the status of just another volunteer, which was fine.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.000
When you applied in fall of 63, was that for the summer,

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:55.000
or were you planning to drop out if they had space for you?

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:58.000
I was supplying for the summer.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:06.000
I had also taken the LSATs and applied to law school.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:15.000
So you were thinking of working with Snick over the summer and then going on the law school before you knew about the summer project?

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:16.000
No.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:27.000
I was thinking initially, I believe, of becoming a civil rights worker and working for Snick or going to law school.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:34.000
And then because they had the summer project, which was a sort of contained thing, you ended up doing both.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:35.000
Right.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:43.000
But during the course of the summer, I debated with myself whether to stay and not go to law school.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:49.000
Because you have the sense that you're just beginning your work, you're just beginning to get the trust of the community.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And how could I just abandon this whole thing and go to law school?

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
How did you make that decision?

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:17.000
The decision was very easily and quickly made when I came home, Pat Vail, and I traveled by bus from Greenville to Summit, New Jersey.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:21.000
Not asking for help from my parents at any point.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:29.000
We took the local bus from Newark to Summit and I knew there was a taxi.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:35.000
The Gettys taxi was right across the street from the bus stop at the train station.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:42.000
And we took the 75 cent taxi with our luggage to the one mile to our house.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:45.000
And my father greeted me at the door.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
And I said, where's mother?

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:53.000
And he said, she's not feeling well.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:01.000
She's learned that you're planning to stay in Mississippi.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:05.000
And I said, I'll go to Stanford.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:21.000
What happened was three students from Greenville went back to New Jersey to recruit delegate support for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party Convention Challenge.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:34.000
And they talked to the press and a reporter asked, or any of the students staying in Mississippi after the summer project.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:40.000
And they said, yes, Lisa Anderson is my mother read that in the paper and she was upset.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:45.000
She was at that point very worried about my safety.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:48.000
And I couldn't take that.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:53.000
So it was bad enough for summer but to have it going continuously was it?

00:44:53.000 --> 00:45:01.000
And it was a difficult summer for them because of the peer pressure, the neighbors and the questions they got.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:04.000
So the neighborhood was not happy.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:17.000
The next door neighbor particularly, my mother didn't want to see her because she was afraid she would bring up the subject of my being in Mississippi.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:21.000
They did form a parents group and I think that was helpful.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:39.000
And also one of my closest friends in high school from a wonderful family, the Sheffield family, and Short Hills, her younger sister Nancy was a volunteer in Greenville.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:52.000
And my mother, I think, spent time talking to Mrs. Sheffield and comparing notes and...

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:56.000
So we kind of jumped ahead.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:00.000
When you knew about the project then you did an application.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:04.000
Did you remember an interview process? Did you interview with someone?

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:13.000
I have fought many times about that interview until I finally realized I never had an interview.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:20.000
And I think based on what I had done the summer before that Jackson decided to accept me for the project.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:24.000
So they had a sense of view and so you didn't have to go through that process?

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:27.000
So but you did go to the orientation in Oxford?

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:30.000
I went late.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:42.000
My graduation was Monday the 15th and I stayed an extra day to go to a friend's wedding on campus in Sage Chapel.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:46.000
I think it was the first wedding I had ever been invited to by friends.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:48.000
And so I thought that was important.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:53.000
And I thought of course that I knew a lot of what was going to be happening at orientation.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:47:00.000
Cornell sponsored a project in Fayette County, Tennessee, Tent City.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:11.000
So there was a group of students driving to Fayette County and I got a ride with them and was dropped off in Oxford.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:15.000
And I think I arrived on Wednesday.

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.000
So Cornell students were active in Fayette County?

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:21.000
Cornell students were active in Fayette County?

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:28.000
Yes, they would volunteer spring vacation, they raised money through student government.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:32.000
So they dropped you off at the orientation?

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:36.000
Was that the, I don't have the dates in my head, was that the first or second week?

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.000
I was there the first week.

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:41.000
So can you describe the orientation?

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:48.000
Bob Moses stood up there and talked to us.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:58.000
And in his modest way, standing kind of on the side and his overalls and clean white t-shirt.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:10.000
And told us just to be there would be important and not to expect to accomplish very much,

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:23.000
to expect that people would be slow and to write to our congressman and to write to our local newspaper

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:34.000
and to tell them what it was like in Mississippi that the word had not reached the rest of the country.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:46.000
And it would be our job to tell the stories in order to first obtain federal protection

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.000
because lives were being lost.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:59.000
And secondly to work a change so that there would be, so that voter registration would become possible.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:09.000
Do you remember any of the rest of the orientation?

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:14.000
We were lectured to about nonviolence.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:20.000
I remember Vincent Harding being so impressive the way he speaks.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:32.000
And I found his remarks are on the internet of what he actually said.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:43.000
I believe it might have been Bruce Hanson who reminded us of our own prejudices that we had to face the fact that

00:49:43.000 --> 00:50:00.000
even though we were going in this great spirit of, there is no difference black people and white people that we might ourselves have in eight prejudice.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:08.000
I remember the role playing we did in nonviolence outside on the lawn.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:19.000
It was a great relief to get outside that auditorium and the reporters and the cameraman participated.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:40.000
And I have a note in the postcard I sent home to my parents I guess that, or else I only have it in my memory but it's a distinct memory that Carl Fleming of Newsweek punched me in the stomach.

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:45.000
And I played of course the role of victim not the role of the role of aggressor.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And I understand the second week of orientation there was very little if any role playing of nonviolence because the mood of course that week changed entirely after the disappearance of what I voice called the three boys.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:13.000
That's the way we talked about the three boys but now everyone, I think very familiar with the fact that

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Cheney, a black,

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:39.000
Schwerner, a staff, of course, staff person and good men of volunteer just like me, not just like me of course, disappeared that Sunday, June, June 21.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:42.000
That's Saturday they disappeared.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.000
Yeah.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.000
The day that I arrived in Mississippi.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
Do you remember how you heard about that?

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:53.000
No, I do not remember exactly how I heard about that.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:54.000
Or your reaction?

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:57.000
I was in Greenville.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:05.000
The reaction is how could that have happened so soon and what does that mean?

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:10.000
That are we all going to be now victimized?

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:16.000
Is that what's going to be happening over and over?

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
How did you end up in Greenville?

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:34.000
I think I ended up there because I was going to be in voter registration and because I had that specific experience in Greensboro and not that I particularly asked for it.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:50.000
And it was dangerous for women, black or white, to be in the fields in most areas of Mississippi.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:53:00.000
Greenville is noted as being a relatively moderate city.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:07.000
So was that something that you were aware of at the time that there was discussion about where women could work in the field?

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
I don't think so.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.000
So that's more something you can think about in retrospect.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:20.000
That I've learned in this period of seven years of trying to write a book and reading.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:26.000
I've read so much now that it's I have to...

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:31.000
I know I have to... I should distinguish my memories and what I do then from what I know now.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:37.000
Yeah, it must be an interesting process.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:53.000
So speaking of what you remember from then and what you know now, I know that one of the things that caused a bit of a stir among conversation, a few years back, was a discussion of attitudes about working in the field.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:57.000
And voter registration work versus freedom school teaching.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:01.000
Did you have any sense of that at the time of status with one or the other?

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:10.000
I felt that I had status.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:30.000
I felt that I was privileged because I was able to have more exposure to black families, black adults to be approaching their homes, not that I was invited inside often.

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:43.000
But I had an opportunity to talk to adults, whereas freedom school teachers were dealing more, I think, in Greenville with young children.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:58.000
I felt that I knew more about the politics of civil rights than the freedom school teachers, who I think they were all white women.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:05.000
So why did you think that you knew more than the teachers from my summer at Tugelow?

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:08.000
So because you'd had more civil rights exposure?

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:11.000
Yes.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:15.000
Who did you work with, Canvassing?

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:27.000
We canvassed as a team, one black and one white, and Pam Trotman, I think I went with often.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:38.000
She was a graduate of Howard, and had been recruited by Stokely Carmichael to come down.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:45.000
She was black.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:52.000
And local high school students, I think, went out with us.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:56:00.000
There were some, I'm thinking of two older men that I canvassed with.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:07.000
One was Charles Moore, and the other was James Williams.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:12.000
Was that a concern for anybody in the project that you're canvassing with black men?

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
No.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:20.000
Who is the project director?

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:24.000
George Rawick was our project director.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.000
He was from the University of Chicago.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:33.000
He was a graduate student, I believe, and he was there for the first month.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:39.000
And then Muriel Tillinghast became the project director.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:52.000
I knew that George was our project director, and I thought that he was not in the SNCC mode of working slowly.

00:56:52.000 --> 00:57:00.000
He was approaching this as a project, as a project that he was going to be the director of.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:06.000
But I always thought that Charles E. Cobb Jr was our project director.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:16.000
He was the project director for Washington County, Issaquena (or Sharkey) County County, and Issaquena County, all three in the region.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:19.000
And he wasn't there very much.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:22.000
He was traveling in the state.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:29.000
I think he was one of the people that went to the show of a county to look for the missing civil rights workers.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:32.000
You thought Charlie was the project director?

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
And he told us what to do.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:37.000
But then you found out in retrospect, like doing research?

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:38.000
Yes.

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:42.000
I found out that Dottie on there when I talked to her on the phone.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:45.000
She said, oh, Muriel was your project director?

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
And I said, oh?

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
How did Daddy know?

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:52.000
Was she relying on memory or documents or both?

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:54.000
Well, it's a fact.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.000
No, I mean, she would know.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:58.000
She knows Muriel, I think, from New York.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:57:59.000
No, I know.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:00.000
I mean, I've talked to her too.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:01.000
I just, you know.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:04.000
Sort of.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:05.000
But that made me realize.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:09.000
And then my friend Pat Veil, she certainly confirmed it.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:16.000
Pat and I got to know each other on the project and have been in touch ever since.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:24.000
Because I think, at least for part of that summer, Muriel was working in Issaquena (or Sharkey) County with...

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:25.000
Issaquena.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
She went to...

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
You need a black one.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:30.000
Right.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:31.000
Right.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
Yeah, she came and went, I think.

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:34.000
Okay.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:35.000
All right.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:38.000
Or else we'd probably operate it without a project director.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:39.000
Yeah.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:40.000
And it's interesting.

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:43.000
I just, because I thought she started there, at least.

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:48.000
And then I interviewed Muriel last summer too.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.000
From my own work.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:58.000
So, what was it like to be in Greenville?

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:00.000
What was it like?

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:05.000
I felt safe.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
I felt less at risk.

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:12.000
I did not feel that courageous what I was doing.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:19.000
We moved in the black community freely.

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:22.000
We never went to the white community.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:30.000
There was no reason to.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.000
And it was hot.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:34.000
Just trying to...

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:39.000
We tried to canvas at any time of the day, all day long.

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:41.000
We lived in community.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.000
That was the most...

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:45.000
Probably the most significant...

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:48.000
One of the most significant parts of the summer for me to be living

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.000
with a black family.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
Who did you live with?

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
I lived in the south end.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:59.000
Well, the first couple of days, the first day I slept on the floor of the Freedom House.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:01.000
There was no housing.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:05.000
But I was confident that Charlie could work the south for us.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:11.000
And there was nothing I could do about it, of course, either.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:13.000
We...

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:22.000
There were three of us stuck together, I think, the whole summer.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
Valerie and Lynn and I.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:31.000
And they were both in research,

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:34.000
whereas I was in voter registration.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:39.000
We got a place to stay with a widow who lived alone across the street in a house

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:43.000
that was just like the Freedom House.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:48.000
And we probably shared a bed in the front room.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:53.000
And I looked forward to taking a bath.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
After a night on the road, we had driven.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:56.000
I had gotten a ride.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:59.000
I didn't go on the bus from Oxford.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:02.000
And we had slept overnight at a house in Memphis.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:06.000
And then the next night I was sleeping on the floor in the Freedom House.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:08.000
And as soon as...

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:14.000
I mean, I can see the depth of the water in the bottom of the tub and the woman yells,

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:18.000
don't use too much water.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
We were out of there in a couple of days.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:25.000
She decided that she did not want the risk of having three white women staying in her house.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:29.000
We went to the home of a woman who I think was more independent.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:36.000
She had a veterans pension income and social security.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:41.000
Her daughter was living with her and she was wonderful.

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:46.000
I just wanted to sit at her kitchen table and hear her stories and talk to her.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
You remember her name?

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:53.000
Mrs. Harden, I think.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:59.000
And there was a boy in the neighborhood.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.000
We went to church with her.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:04.000
And there was a boy in the neighborhood who said,

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:09.000
Uncle Tom's are trying to run her out of church because she took you to church.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:12.000
I thought that was terrible.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:16.000
I moved from there because that was on the south end.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:22.000
And our voter registration office was on Nelson Street in the north end.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:31.000
The three of us lived with Jerry and Lamar Britton.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:38.000
And they had a large brick air conditioned house.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:46.000
And Valerie and I had a double bed room on the first floor.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:49.000
And this place was open house for us.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:51.000
It was wonderful.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.000
How did they do?

01:02:53.000 --> 01:03:00.000
They owned a drugstore at the corner of North and Nelson.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:03.000
And they both worked in the store.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:13.000
And Mrs. Britten lay on the couch in the den.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.000
The house was very open.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:19.000
The kitchen and the eating area and this den area.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:23.000
And then we had this room off the side.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:31.000
And she said, don't ever get those hot flashes.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:35.000
You're like, I'm in Mississippi in the summer.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:42.000
What are you talking about?

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:48.000
What are Valerie and Lynn's last names?

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
Lynn Hamilton.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:54.000
And I just had to look up Valerie's last name.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:04:02.000
And I want to say Horton, but I'm not sure that's correct.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:08.000
So did you have a routine where every day you'd get up at a certain time and head out to the campus?

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:10.000
No. No routine.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:11.000
No routine.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:18.000
We went to the office and we divvied up the city, you know, the areas.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:21.000
So we weren't overlapping each other.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:24.000
So you were pretty much working in the city of Greenville?

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:25.000
Yes.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:27.000
A little bit outside.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:30.000
But we had a transportation problem.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:31.000
That's what I was going to ask.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:32.000
Were you walking pretty much?

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:33.000
Yes.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:40.000
If you could get a free ride probably with a black taxi driver.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:49.000
So when you go door to door, did you, what was the experience like when you're asking people about registering?

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:56.000
Pretty much neutral, non-committal, not interested.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:00.000
You know, life is okay, status quo.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:04.000
There wasn't a strong response.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:10.000
What it turned into very quickly was not typical voter registration.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:23.000
We want you to go to the courthouse to register, but to, but freedom registration for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party, which was the alternative.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:31.000
So I had a clipboard with, and I have a picture of me carrying the clipboard.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:35.000
Some photographer was behind Pam and me one day.

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:36.000
Yeah.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:37.000
Took a picture.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:38.000
That's great picture.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:39.000
Yeah.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:49.000
Would you register for the Freedom Democratic Party and fill out this form?

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:52.000
And anybody could register.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:06:00.000
You were not required to be literate even, just to be able to sign your own name.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:04.000
And we had to explain the Freedom Democratic Party.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:08.000
And so that would be, that would be the nature of my canvassing.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:12.000
Did you have better response to the request for freedom registration?

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:13.000
Yes.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.000
Yes.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:15.000
Yes.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:21.000
We had to assure people that this was not going to become public knowledge.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:27.000
And unlike, unlike applying an application for voter registration,

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:35.000
you didn't just register to vote, you had to apply and qualify through the literacy tests,

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:42.000
including the interpretation of the Mississippi State Constitution provision that happened to be given to you,

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:46.000
to the satisfaction of the registrar who had complete discretion.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:56.000
And then publicity of your name in the new, local newspaper for two weeks to test your more,

01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:57.000
moral character.

01:06:57.000 --> 01:07:03.000
That meant everyone knew who was seeking to register to vote.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:08.000
And that was such a deterrent, I think, for people.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:15.000
So your impression is that people were much more willing because there was more protection around the Freedom Registration, more privacy?

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:25.000
We were more apt to get somebody to sign that Freedom Registration Forum by saying

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:28.000
this forum is not going to go anywhere.

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:29.000
We're going to keep the forum.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:32.000
I mean, I think that would still be a risk for somebody.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:42.000
But that was our accomplishment was to go back to the office with signed Freedom Registration Forms.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:51.000
So who did you report to when you would come back when you would go in the morning or when you'd come back with the forms?

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:53.000
Who would you hand them off to?

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:56.000
I have no recollection.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:03.000
I guess it was probably Pat who filled in.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:08.000
Pat was went down from...

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:20.000
She had been working as a legal secretary as a secretary in the law school at Harvard when she heard about the Mississippi summer project and applied.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:24.000
And she was assigned to be a Freedom School teacher.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
But she knew how to type.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:32.000
So she became the Freedom Secretary and worked in the office.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:37.000
And she would have kept track of that kind of thing.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:45.000
So some people have talked about issues of black deference to white volunteers during canvassing and stuff like that.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:47.000
Did you experience that?

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:50.000
That was why we went out as a team, as a black and white team.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:09:04.000
We did not want people to agree to register just because it was a white asking for that to be done and to defer to an authority figure.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:05.000
Yeah.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:13.000
So you mentioned earlier that because of your experience in Greensboro, you'd had experience with relationships with black men.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:17.000
And so that wasn't a big deal for you in the summer of 64.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:22.000
Do you remember it being an issue on the project for other people?

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:26.000
The only...

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:28.000
No.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:29.000
No.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:42.000
The only thing I remember in terms of what about the sex on the project is that one of the white volunteers left.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:46.000
And the word was that she was pregnant.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:53.000
And she left with a black volunteer.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:58.000
Now how she knew that fast that she was pregnant, I don't know.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
You see?

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:03.000
Are you ready, John?

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:05.000
You mentioned Charles E. Cobb Jr.

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:08.000
Did you met him in 63 when you were in Mississippi?

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:09.000
No.

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:11.000
Or do you know him then through the summer project?

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:21.000
So after you did the Freedom Registration, were you involved in the precinct meetings or any of that groundwork with the FTP?

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:23.000
Yes.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:27.000
We were...

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:37.000
There were six precincts in Greenville where we elected precinct delegates.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:40.000
And I was in charge of one of those precincts.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:42.000
And we had...

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:49.000
We didn't just have a precinct meeting, but we had a workshop before the precinct meeting to...

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:54.000
For people to understand what the process was going to be.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:58.000
And I can't just...

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:04.000
With Mr. Williams the day of the workshop, I believe.

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:10.000
And maybe we had 12 people at his house or at a neighbor's house.

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:14.000
But at the precinct meeting we got 20 people.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:16.000
And I thought that was pretty good.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:26.000
Although I had been scornful earlier in the summer when Freedom School teachers came back from an NAACP meeting and saying that they were ready to move.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:28.000
And that there were 20 people there.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:29.000
I thought, no, no, no.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:32.000
You know, the NAACP, they're not moving.

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:33.000
We need to...

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:40.000
We need to find new people who will be more aggressive working towards civil rights.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:45.000
At the precinct we elected delegates to the county convention.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:50.000
And then I went to the county convention.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:55.000
And was very interested in the way that was conducted.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:12:02.000
Because there was a local man, Mr. Chappell, who was active in the Democratic Party.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:09.000
I think, who decided that he could run this meeting better than the Neophytes.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:15.000
The new people coming into politics that had been recruited by the MFDP.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:21.000
And he tried to get a chairman elected.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:24.000
And that didn't work.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:35.000
But then he moved that all the precinct delegates who were present should be elected county delegates.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:42.000
And managed to get that seconded and passed.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:48.000
And this is local people who are looking to...

01:12:48.000 --> 01:13:02.000
They're traditional leaders, and tending to listen to them, as opposed to thinking about what the alternatives are and pushing for an alternative.

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:11.000
And so what I noted in a letter home was he got a strange bunch in there.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And there were some people that were very strong with the MFDP that we had been working with who were then elected county delegates.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:38.000
And the comment that I got from a couple women at the end of that meeting was they step in at the end, but where were they when we were doing all the work.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:40.000
They were resentful.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:46.000
And I was glad to hear that expression of opinion because that was my opinion.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:58.000
So the delegation from Greenville or from Washington County included then some of the traditional leaders because of that.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:13:59.000
Yes.

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:02.000
And then some of the newer leaders.

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:09.000
And the women who had been more active with SNCC and the FDP were not happy about that combination.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:16.000
Do you remember who some of the strong local leaders were that were working with SNCC and the FDP?

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:28.000
Well, Dorothy Jones was worked for the Hodding Carter family.

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:39.000
And was one of the people, Edna Morton, the housed volunteers and Pat knew her quite well.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:45.000
Willie Rollins, I believe, was elected then.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:50.000
I can't think of other names.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:55.000
Were women more involved in the FDP than men?

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:59.000
In Greenville.

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:00.000
I think so.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:02.000
That's your impression.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:09.000
Did you think about that at the time or did you have any sense of how that?

01:15:09.000 --> 01:15:13.000
No, it wasn't.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:21.000
That's something that you know, you historians think about in retrospect.

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:35.000
And the explanation for why women were more able to stand up to the pressures that men were going to be lynched.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:47.000
If they did it, and women were more likely to be not respected but allowed to do something for civil rights.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.000
I'm just curious if it's something that you thought about at all at the time.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:56.000
Some people did and some people didn't.

01:15:56.000 --> 01:16:02.000
Did you then follow the Greenville delegation to the Jackson Convention?

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:04.000
Well, you skipped a step.

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:06.000
There was a district clock.

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:08.000
Who was the district clock?

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:10.000
Second district.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:13.000
It's the congressional districts.

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:14.000
Yes.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:16.000
And it was the Delta.

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:18.000
And it was held in Greenville.

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:22.000
We met at the Friendship Baptist Church, which was formerly a movie theater.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:24.000
It was a big place.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:29.000
And they came in on Sunday and Fannie Lou Hamer led the singing.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:31.000
And it was fabulous.

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:33.000
Had you seen her since the summer before?

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:36.000
No, but I saw her that day.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:42.000
And you know, recalled my being at her home and she gave me a big hug.

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:43.000
Yeah.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:45.000
It was a highlight.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:46.000
Yeah.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:55.000
So that must have been probably one of the most important district meetings then, the second district.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:17:00.000
Well, I don't know how it would compare to the others because the Delta had the Delta.

01:17:00.000 --> 01:17:04.000
She would have had the strongest FDP presence.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:05.000
Right.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:13.000
So these meetings was this mirroring the normal Democratic Party, the congressional district

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:14.000
solves it.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:17.000
It was pretty creating a shadow.

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:18.000
Yes.

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:29.000
The Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party was established to parallel the Mississippi Democratic Party.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:39.000
And we set up procedures that would match completely what was required by state law.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:42.000
And it's...

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:48.000
Do you remember people in Greenville trying to go to the regular Democratic precinct meetings?

01:17:48.000 --> 01:17:49.000
No.

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:50.000
That was before.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:51.000
Okay.

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:52.000
That would have been an early June.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:53.000
Okay.

01:17:53.000 --> 01:17:55.000
So that was before you were in...

01:17:55.000 --> 01:17:57.000
Did you know that their experience was?

01:17:57.000 --> 01:18:03.000
I believe that's correct.

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:12.000
They were admitted and in one precinct they passed a resolution of support for the national

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:17.000
ticket, the national candidates in ticket.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:18.000
Okay.

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:23.000
So what else do you remember from the district meeting besides Miss Haymer leading the singing and

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:26.000
getting to see her again?

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:36.000
I remember that I was so enthusiastic that this was going to work, that to see people participating

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:41.000
in politics and it was very exciting.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:47.000
How did the delegate selection process go at that stage?

01:18:47.000 --> 01:19:02.000
I remember specifically, but the district caucus was not electing delegates but was coming

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:09.000
up with a recommended list of delegates that would go to the state convention and the state

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:15.000
convention would actually elect the 68 delegates who would go to the national convention

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:17.000
in Atlantic City.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:31.000
And I believe then at the district caucus I was pleased that Mr. Chapel did not get recommended

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:34.000
as a delegate.

01:19:34.000 --> 01:19:42.000
I was afraid that he would undercut the new MFDP people.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:44.000
But he wasn't successful at that stage.

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:51.000
Right. But at the state convention I learned somehow that he got nominated by another district

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:54.000
but he did not get elected to go to Atlantic City.

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:56.000
Was he at the state convention?

01:19:56.000 --> 01:19:59.000
He managed to get to the state convention.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:02.000
He was in the city on other business.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:05.000
He didn't want to let it go.

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:08.000
What was his position in Greenville?

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:12.000
He had a printing business. He was a successful businessman.

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:21.000
There are oral interviews in the William Alexander Percy Memorial Library (Greenville MS) in Greenville, which we've

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:23.000
just fascinating.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:28.000
One of them telling me what Mrs. Britton thought of me.

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:32.000
What did you think of you?

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:42.000
That the volunteers were not hippie scruffy kids, whatever words she used there, but were

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:43.000
nice.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:50.000
She worried about us coming home at night, but she didn't worry about herself and the house or

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:51.000
anything.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:54.000
She gave us free reign.

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:57.000
Sometimes she even clicked in her for us.

01:20:57.000 --> 01:21:05.000
That fall her husband died and she said that everyone on the project sent her a note.

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:12.000
That the following summer I stopped in the drugstore to say hello to her and I was well

01:21:12.000 --> 01:21:15.000
dressed then.

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:20.000
I hadn't been the summer before you know.

01:21:20.000 --> 01:21:23.000
When were these oral histories done?

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:25.000
1978 I think.

01:21:25.000 --> 01:21:27.000
How was it done?

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:33.000
Daisy Bates or somebody.

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:38.000
Many of the people she interviewed were school teachers.

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:40.000
I understand.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:46.000
Many people that were important to the movement she did not interview.

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:52.000
Her daughter William Alexander Percy Memorial Library (Greenville MS) is in Greenville and has not been very cooperative in letting

01:21:52.000 --> 01:21:59.000
go of whatever additional material she has.

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:03.000
The same interviews are also in the state archives.

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:06.000
Our publicist duplicate copy.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:09.000
Interesting.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:13.000
That they were done that early.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:16.000
Sort of collection.

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:19.000
So you were at the state convention?

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:20.000
No, I was not.

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:26.000
For a while I thought I was.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:34.000
But I read in a letter that the first question was there was a meeting that evening in Greenville

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:38.000
that I went to and I said how could I have done both on the same day.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:44.000
Then I saw a reference that I was writing letters and ironing that afternoon.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:47.000
So I was not at the state convention.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:50.000
But I read about it so many times I had the same.

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:53.000
You felt like you were there and you felt you remembered it?

01:22:53.000 --> 01:22:59.000
Let me interject one thing about Charles E. Cobb Jr.

01:22:59.000 --> 01:23:13.000
What he told us to do was to in all of our recruiting for voter registration to work around the local leaders.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:39.000
It dawned on me later that what he was saying was that we were to be finding new voices and that and allowing new people to stand up and speak up on their own behalf rather than continuing to defer to establish the established leadership.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:44.000
That is what we now call empowerment.

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:51.000
We were empowering people and I don't think we ever used that word.

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:58.000
And it's just like, well everything you read now about the beloved community.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:24:00.000
We never talked about the beloved community.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:18.000
That we were living in that near ideal state of where class and race and economic status make no difference that we're all part of the human family.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:21.000
So that characterization comes later?

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:41.000
No, it comes from Martin Luther King, far earlier that he wrote about it as the outgrowth of nonviolence and reconciliation that we would eventually arrive at the beloved community that that was our goal.

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:55.000
Did you have any sense in your interactions with SNCC and in the summer about the sort of different views on nonviolence and those sorts of ideas that have been debated in the group at different points?

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:05.000
Yes, we had some some militant black guys on the project who were talking.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:16.000
Who were not who were talking about the possibility of violence?

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:19.000
In terms of retaliation, in terms of self defense.

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:34.000
Not self defense, but just the anger, the anger, the lack of optimism, the feeling of helplessness that there's, you know,

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:37.000
this nonviolence stuff is not working.

01:25:37.000 --> 01:25:42.000
Now, are these folks who are SNCC staff or local people or volunteers?

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:52.000
They were, I wondered what their status was.

01:25:52.000 --> 01:25:56.000
They were, they appeared to be SNCC staff.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:00.000
They were assigned by cofo Jackson to Greenville.

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:09.000
They were, I think, both new to the community college students.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:17.000
And they were, they spoke anti-Bab Moses that he doesn't know, he doesn't know what's going on.

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:21.000
You know, he's on his way out of the movement.

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:25.000
That they, they knew, you know, what, what, what needed to be done.

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:30.000
We, we had a demonstration the first week on the project.

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:40.000
We, and this was instigated by the local chapter of the Mississippi Student Union, the high school students.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:49.000
And they wanted to, after we heard about the disappearance of the three civil rights workers,

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:54.000
they wanted to demonstrate for federal protection.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:00.000
And we picketed at the federal building midday.

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:06.000
And I prepared to be arrested for the first time.

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:11.000
And, you know, had my toothbrush or something in my pocket.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:17.000
And nothing happened. The police looked on, the, the passersby looked on.

01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:27.000
We were out there for a couple of hours. But we were clearly instructed during orientation, not to demonstrate.

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:36.000
And when Bob Moses in Oxford heard that there was a demonstration in Greenville, he said, that's not true.

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:42.000
Couldn't, that couldn't be. I have that, I have that in one of my letters.

01:27:43.000 --> 01:27:46.000
So did you all get it?

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:53.000
But what I was leading to was these, these two fellows wanted to have a demonstration the next week.

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:58.000
You know, they wanted to, I think, demonstrate at the,

01:27:58.000 --> 01:28:05.000
at the black swimming pool that whites should be able to swim in the black swimming pool.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:13.000
And I was supposed to that. You know, I thought we, maybe we could tell Jackson that we wanted to do it.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:19.000
And if they, if cofo and Jackson said, okay, then that'd be okay, but, but we should not do that.

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:22.000
How did that get resolved?

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:25.000
It didn't happen. It got dropped.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:32.000
But I think the, but there was a later demonstration at the federal building.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:41.000
And that's the subject of, of one of the letters from Mississippi that Barbara Mutnick wrote.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:45.000
What was that demonstration about? What was the second demonstration?

01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:48.000
The same, I think, that was also for federal protection.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:57.000
And the idea was if, if local people wanted to demonstrate, were we going to say, oh, we, we can't do that.

01:28:57.000 --> 01:29:02.000
Well, were we going to support them because we wanted their support?

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:13.000
And do you remember were there discussions with sort of longer term cofo staff about the first demonstration or the second one because of the, that very dilemma?

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:23.000
We had long discussions about whether to demonstrate and whether we should apply for a permit.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:29.000
And one of these fellows called up the police chief and said, we're going to be there in 15 minutes.

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:37.000
So that's how that was decided.

01:29:37.000 --> 01:29:39.000
But, yeah, okay.

01:29:39.000 --> 01:29:45.000
So this was mainly, so that the impetus for the demonstrations is the same guys that are talking about violence.

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:49.000
The ones that you said came from the Jackson through the cofo.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:53.000
They and that with the high school students, the high school students.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:58.000
Yeah. I mean, I know that there were tensions in Greenwood about demonstrations and sort of,

01:29:58.000 --> 01:30:03.000
Smith was being called conservative for not wanting to demonstrate in Greenwood that summer.

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:09.000
So that exact tension that you described.

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:14.000
So are there other things that stand out for you from that summer that you remember?

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:22.000
Well, somebody asked me once, what did we do for fun?

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:25.000
And I had to think about that.

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:27.000
What was fun during that summer?

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:37.000
I felt that I was working very hard, that I was very committed to this work.

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:47.000
The one way to respond to that was, well, and somebody else said it to me first.

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:57.000
But what I enjoyed was sitting in one of these cafes over a meal, sharing a quarter of beer and talking.

01:30:57.000 --> 01:31:00.000
In a group, it wasn't going to be Charles E. Cobb Jr.

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:02.000
He never joined our group.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:11.000
And I don't know who the interesting local blacks were because it wasn't just us white volunteers there.

01:31:11.000 --> 01:31:18.000
But just to talk about what are we doing, what should we be doing, what's going on?

01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:23.000
Not that we were great strategists or anything and could influence things.

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:26.000
But we were so involved in the issues of civil rights.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:37.000
We had one event on the 4th of July, Dr. (Matthew T.) Frisbee.

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:53.000
Invited all the project volunteers, and I think there were 35 of us, to his home for a picnic, barbecue picnic, and the neighbors were there.

01:31:53.000 --> 01:32:00.000
And that was a very nice occasion where we got to see one another because we had separated throughout the city.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:05.000
And answer questions from local people.

01:32:05.000 --> 01:32:12.000
These were the middle class, well to do established people in Greenville.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:28.000
But the other thing that when I've contacted the volunteers recently, that we all remember, is the time that we were invited to swim in Hodding Carter's pool.

01:32:28.000 --> 01:32:41.000
And this was Dorothy Jones and she asked me if I would like to stay overnight because the Carter's were going out of town and she didn't want to be alone with the baby.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:48.000
And then bring along some people and you can swim.

01:32:48.000 --> 01:32:53.000
Well it's quickly turned into the whole project going over to swim.

01:32:53.000 --> 01:33:03.000
And the girls I've talked to were trying to remember, we didn't go down to Greenville with our bathing suits, how did we?

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:08.000
What did we do? One person thought that they had bathing suits that we could use in the pool house.

01:33:08.000 --> 01:33:14.000
And somebody else said we'd probably just strip down and swam on our shorts and our clothes.

01:33:14.000 --> 01:33:24.000
And this was delightful.

01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:38.000
Suddenly the party was broken up by two or three men riding into the property on horseback.

01:33:38.000 --> 01:33:45.000
And apparently the neighbors thought something strange was going on and they were there to protect the Carter's.

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:56.000
And we quickly disbanded, got back to the project somehow, with whatever little transportation we had.

01:33:56.000 --> 01:34:05.000
But Barbara and Nancy did stay overnight and they would never do this of course in somebody's house.

01:34:05.000 --> 01:34:13.000
But they opened the drawer of the nightstand by the bed and there was a revolver in there.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:20.000
And Barbara wrote in the letter that the place was fully armed. It was like an arsenal.

01:34:20.000 --> 01:34:26.000
One revolver? I don't know what else she saw.

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:31.000
Did Dorothy Jones face repercussions for throwing this pool party?

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:37.000
No, that was with consent and I've talked to Hodding Carter about it.

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:43.000
And Charles E. Cobb Jr referred to it in his interview at Southern Mississippi.

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:44.000
So he remembered it too?

01:34:44.000 --> 01:34:46.000
Everybody remembers it.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:49.000
It was a major event of the summer.

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:56.000
I mean, can you imagine being a swimming pool when you're a civil rights worker in Mississippi the summer of 1964?

01:34:56.000 --> 01:34:58.000
Nope.

01:34:58.000 --> 01:35:01.000
Nope, pretty much not.

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:10.000
Pat tells me that she used to go downtown and walk into a bank to cool off in the air conditioning.

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:13.000
I can see that.

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:17.000
But I went downtown by myself once to buy something.

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:18.000
I've found my way.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:21.000
We were not supposed to be traveling alone ever.

01:35:21.000 --> 01:35:23.000
Did you feel restricted by that?

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:26.000
No.

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:30.000
You mentioned a comment earlier by Johnny Frazier.

01:35:30.000 --> 01:35:34.000
And he said you were getting ahead is now a good time to...

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:42.000
Right, right. Well, what's interesting about Johnny Frazier is that I learned from...

01:35:42.000 --> 01:35:47.000
I think I learned from Hodding Carter.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:54.000
But somehow I put together Johnny Frazier, who I met in 1963.

01:35:54.000 --> 01:35:59.000
He spoke to our group besides speaking at a mass meeting that we went to.

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:07.000
He was the head of the NAACP Youth Chapter that he was from Greenville.

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:25.000
And he was... when he was a student at Coleman High School, he wore a black arm band to school because of the Brown versus Board of Education decision.

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:34.000
In mourning that they were not doing anything about it or whatever his theory was, but he was suspended.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:41.000
And Hodding Carter apparently wrote an editorial about this and they met.

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:51.000
But he was allowed back into the school because his aunt said that...

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:59.000
Well, they'd sued to integrate the White High School if they wouldn't let him back into the black one.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:03.000
It's good to know what the levers work, isn't it?

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:18.000
But his daughter, I think, Nishani Frazier, is at Miami University and she's been a sponsor of the reunions.

01:37:18.000 --> 01:37:26.000
And I saw him there somehow. I don't know that I identified him, but whether he had a name tag on or something, then I said,

01:37:26.000 --> 01:37:31.000
are you the Johnny Frazier from Greenville and Jackson?

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:46.000
And I told him that I was trying to write up my story in retirement and he gave me a big bear hug and thank you for what you did to open things up.

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:49.000
That's what the summer project did.

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:56.000
The other person who did that for me is Dory Ladner and I'll never forget that.

01:37:56.000 --> 01:38:03.000
And that was many years ago when I don't know what the year that Freedom on My Mind came out.

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:11.000
That would have been about 94. It was either fall 94 or spring 95.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:22.000
See, I was working. I was not involved at all in civil rights activities or recollections or anything.

01:38:22.000 --> 01:38:32.000
But I knew that the film was being shown at the Biograph Theater and there was just a gathering of people.

01:38:32.000 --> 01:38:39.000
I remember Heather Booth was there and she was saying hello to Sen. Paul Simon.

01:38:39.000 --> 01:38:47.000
I remember that. That's when I first met Dory or knew that Dory was in Washington.

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:53.000
So had you known Dory from Mississippi? No. She wasn't in Attu, who that summer, I don't think.

01:38:53.000 --> 01:38:56.000
So what did Dory, so you met her at that time?

01:38:56.000 --> 01:39:03.000
She said, I said I was a summer volunteer in 1964 and she said thank you.

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:10.000
Have you stayed in touch or seen her on a number of occasions?

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:21.000
I think Johnny Frazier was on a list of names, one of the lists of names that Bob Moses was sending back to Jane Stembridge in summer of 1960 of the people that he met.

01:39:21.000 --> 01:39:33.000
When he was touring, looking for contacts in Alabama, Mississippi and anyway, Johnny Frazier was one of the young people he identified back in summer of 1960.

01:39:33.000 --> 01:39:38.000
So you said you were at the Democratic National Convention? You didn't just make that memory up?

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:42.000
That's great for, okay, that's right in the city.

01:39:42.000 --> 01:39:54.000
I decided early on that I wanted to go to the convention and because Atlantic City is just a couple hours from summer, it would be feasible.

01:39:54.000 --> 01:40:11.000
So Pat and I went to our house, stayed overnight and drove down to Atlantic City and missed entirely Saturday, Fannie Lou Hamers testimony, didn't see it on television.

01:40:11.000 --> 01:40:33.000
We did have a television at that time and stayed in the church of Union Baptist Temple Church where the meetings were held of the MFDP delegation.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:55.000
We slept there and spent our days walking on the boardwalk, talking to delegates, urging them to vote Cross-corpus with Guyot #76.P3.13 the MFDP delegation or we were participating in the visuals and the rallies outside convention hall.

01:40:55.000 --> 01:41:06.000
Was something like that? You know, you decided you wanted to be there and it wasn't too far from your home. Is there any kind of, you know, do you have an official role there?

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:13.000
Is there any kind of effort by the project to decide who's going to be there and who's not or what work people are doing at this point?

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:25.000
Well, the project I think recruited people in August, recruited volunteers to work with their state delegations.

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:35.000
Now, I had three people doing that in New Jersey who left the project early to go back to find New Jersey delegates.

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:46.000
Now, I didn't know any delegates, democratic delegates to the convention, so I didn't feel that I had that role.

01:41:46.000 --> 01:41:57.000
And the other thing that's interesting is that Pat and I didn't make any effort to find a role for ourselves.

01:41:57.000 --> 01:42:06.000
We were freelance. We knew what we were supposed to do was to get the delegation seated, however we could.

01:42:06.000 --> 01:42:25.000
But we didn't look for the organizer of that effort. And I have learned that Ella Baker was really putting together the state delegation support

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:48.000
from the Washington office of the MFDP. And Ella and her homes was working with her, particularly after she finished writing the brief for Joseph L. Rauh Jr.

01:42:48.000 --> 01:43:07.000
And Ella and her told me last month or whatever when I interviewed her that Ella said to her, I really don't want to do this to organize the lobbying operation.

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:36.000
Would you do it for me? So she was at the gem hotel where the delegation stayed and where Charlene Cranston Young, snake volunteer secretary from in Washington, was organizing the transportation to get the delegates to out to meet state caucuses and individuals.

01:43:36.000 --> 01:43:50.000
Members of the credentials committee to get support. Pat and I never went to the gem hotel. I didn't even heard the gem hotel when I was there.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:44:04.000
But we were at the church. We were doing our own thing, walking around on our own. And every time we heard there was a meeting at the church.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:25.000
And we went to those open meetings. So that was Tuesday afternoon, after the credentials committee voted the symbolic two-seat offer.

01:44:25.000 --> 01:44:48.000
And on Wednesday, after the convention adopted the credentials committee decision. And the Johnson administration wanted the delegation to reconsider its refusal of that offer.

01:44:48.000 --> 01:44:59.000
And we couldn't get a seat. There were so many people. I can remember standing in an outside aisle listening to this fascinating discussion.

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:09.000
Where these prominent, prominent people were saying this is a great deal. Take the deal. This is fabulous. And they called it the compromise.

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:23.000
There was no compromise because there were not two sides, each with a position that came together and each side gave up something and they reached an agreement. There was no agreement.

01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:32.000
So what did you, what was it like to sit there and hear all those people prominent people, civil rights supporters taking those positions?

01:45:32.000 --> 01:45:54.000
I felt like I was in on history. I don't know that I saw historical significance. But I was seeing these Senator Wayne Morse and Bayard Rustin, of course, was the eloquent speaker. But not persuasive.

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:59.000
I knew that the MFDP should be seated.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:06.000
How did, do you remember how the MFDP delegates responded? Were you there when I?

01:46:06.000 --> 01:46:23.000
I recall that very few of them spoke up in the open discussion. And so it may be that they spoke up when it was closed, when after the only people in the delegation went to a different room.

01:46:23.000 --> 01:46:30.000
Everybody says that we were evicted from the big room. They moved to a different room.

01:46:30.000 --> 01:46:37.000
And it was very clear that there were only 68 people there. And so at that point, and that's how we all waited in the big room.

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:41.000
And finally somebody came out and said they voted no.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:48.000
So that's small meeting when it's just the delegates. So at that point people like Ella Baker and Bob Moses aren't there either?

01:46:48.000 --> 01:47:03.000
Correct. Absolutely. Nobody there. What I've learned is that the credentials committee supporters, the last supporters that came on Tuesday afternoon after the vote.

01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:17.000
And I think Rep. Edith Green apparently spoke. I distinctly remember that Martin Luther King was not allowed to speak. That he was, he was hushed, hushed out.

01:47:17.000 --> 01:47:26.000
But they met separately. And they agreed to keep their discussions confidential.

01:47:26.000 --> 01:47:35.000
So tell me, so what are we talking about now? Tuesday afternoon after the credentials committee decision.

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:41.000
So after the decision where everybody's back at the church and everybody's back at the church.

01:47:42.000 --> 01:47:49.000
And the delegates learn the decision from Joseph L. Rauh Jr. And he says, I recommend you support if.

01:47:49.000 --> 01:47:51.000
All right. What?

01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:55.000
And then at that point you said King wasn't allowed to speak?

01:47:55.000 --> 01:48:01.000
Correct. On Tuesday afternoon. On Tuesday afternoon. And then what was the part about Rep. Edith Green and the other supporters?

01:48:01.000 --> 01:48:13.000
Oh yeah. Then they came from their meeting to the church. And they got themselves together. They had a little meeting somewhere.

01:48:13.000 --> 01:48:24.000
And what were they, what were they going to do? Were they going to still try to file a minority report?

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:32.000
And then they agreed to keep those discussions confidential. But they ultimately didn't do a minority report.

01:48:32.000 --> 01:48:40.000
Correct. Because they, because Joseph L. Rauh Jr decided that they, he didn't have the numbers. Aaron Henry said they had 10.

01:48:40.000 --> 01:48:51.000
Joseph L. Rauh Jr says they had, I think he said, I think, I think he had eight.

01:48:52.000 --> 01:48:55.000
And he didn't want to look for three more.

01:48:55.000 --> 01:49:05.000
What is your sense of Rao's role in all of it since you've been, I guess before I asked that question, we should say that you've been doing research.

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:11.000
So that, so part of this is your memory and part of this is the research that you've been doing for quite a while now.

01:49:11.000 --> 01:49:17.000
Right. Right. That's focused pretty much on the FDP and the challenge, right? Is that a fair characterization?

01:49:17.000 --> 01:49:19.000
Yes. But how it's evolved.

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:21.000
Why don't you say how the project is?

01:49:21.000 --> 01:49:31.000
Okay. What the project is, what happened? When I retired in April, April 1, 2006, seven years ago.

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:41.000
And I retired in order to write something that was more interesting than the writing that I had been doing in my work.

01:49:42.000 --> 01:49:55.000
And I talked to a couple people who were writers, friends from high school, and they asked me questions like, who's your audience?

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:10.000
Why, what's your purpose? Why are you doing this? And they suggested, and this was good advice, I think, to write a memoir, to write it as fast as I could from my memory.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:19.000
And to get my letters transcribed.

01:50:24.000 --> 01:50:32.000
And my diary also transcribed. And I had a former secretary who was able to do that for me.

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:37.000
And so by August 1, I had something.

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:38.000
Wow.

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:51.000
And because what I wanted to, the reason I wanted to write was not to write a memoir about my story of what I did during the Mississippi summer project.

01:50:52.000 --> 01:51:03.000
But I wanted to write about the MFDP convention challenge to find out why we lost.

01:51:03.000 --> 01:51:11.000
What happened? What was going on? Because I didn't understand it, and I left disillusioned.

01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:17.000
And that's when the questions got hard about, you know, what are you trying to do?

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:23.000
And I couldn't explain myself very well, so I proceeded along this memoir route.

01:51:23.000 --> 01:51:29.000
And I only read Taylor Branch's summary of what happened in Atlantic City, and I got an idea.

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:38.000
But then I started reading more and got confused.

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:50.000
And with the sequence of events, and my first research I think was at UNC in Anne Romaine's oral interviews.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:56.000
And that made me want to do more. And then my niece was getting her PhD at the University of Texas.

01:51:56.000 --> 01:52:07.000
And so I went down and stayed with them and went to the LBJ library and learned about the Johnson tapes of his conversations.

01:52:08.000 --> 01:52:13.000
And I was really excited about the questions that you can listen to very easily on the internet.

01:52:13.000 --> 01:52:24.000
And that was incredibly eye-opening. And then I just kept working on the story of Atlantic City.

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:33.000
I produced a research paper that with 250 pages called New Perceptions Atlantic City Revisited.

01:52:34.000 --> 01:52:41.000
And I was impressed, but he said, it really needs editing too much detail.

01:52:41.000 --> 01:52:48.000
No, I think it was repetitive. It was all over the lot. And I was hurrying.

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:53.000
I wanted to get something done. I wanted to get something circulated.

01:52:53.000 --> 01:53:02.000
I wanted to send it to some people to read. And I was going to have surgery in March of 2008.

01:53:02.000 --> 01:53:09.000
And I swear I sent it in the mail the day before I went to New Orleans for surgery.

01:53:09.000 --> 01:53:17.000
So then I tried to put both stories together.

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:25.000
And then I got told I had a hybrid that didn't work either way. And then I kept pursuing it.

01:53:25.000 --> 01:53:37.000
But I did more and more research. And then our friend John Dittmer advised me that the writing that he read required footnotes.

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:51.000
And so that's been my last effort to footnote all the material. And in the course of doing that, to realize the omissions, the things that I still don't have in the manuscript.

01:53:51.000 --> 01:54:00.000
So what are some of the pieces that you still don't have? What are some of the pieces that you still don't have?

01:54:00.000 --> 01:54:20.000
A single document, for example, there's a letter about the sit-ins on the convention floor that's somewhere in the LBJ documents that I have somewhere on my computer that said why they decided to do that.

01:54:20.000 --> 01:54:27.000
They decided to allow the sit-ins to go forward. They did not want a televised confrontation.

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:33.000
I'm here to respect those trucks in the air guy in this floor.

01:54:33.000 --> 01:54:53.000
Johnson opposed the seating of the Freedom Democrats because the traditional answer is that he was afraid of losing southern electoral votes and afraid of losing the election to Barry Goldwater,

01:54:53.000 --> 01:55:02.000
who was the most frightening man that could possibly have become president of the United States.

01:55:02.000 --> 01:55:13.000
And it's more than that, though, I've discovered because the riots had begun in Rochester and Harlem. That's summer already, summer of 1964.

01:55:14.000 --> 01:55:20.000
And the term backlash was in our lexicon.

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:30.000
And Johnson did not want the election to be about race. That would have been the only way he could have lost or come close to losing.

01:55:31.000 --> 01:55:37.000
And it was a fear of losing white votes throughout the country.

01:55:37.000 --> 01:55:44.000
And he did not want any black delegates on the floor of the convention.

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:51.000
And he didn't want that in part on the advice of his friend, Governor John Gov. John Connally of Texas.

01:55:51.000 --> 01:55:55.000
And he did not want to lose his Texas votes.

01:55:55.000 --> 01:56:02.000
And he was already in trouble because he had supported the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

01:56:02.000 --> 01:56:08.000
So what is your take on Rao's role?

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:17.000
The challenge would not have gone forward without Rao. He was critically important.

01:56:17.000 --> 01:56:38.000
He claims that he lined up the state delegation support. He and his politically savvy people, not the SNCC workers like Frank Smith, Reggie Robinson, and Leslie McLemore who were working out of the Washington office that summer.

01:56:38.000 --> 01:56:45.000
And he did a brilliant job at the credentials committee hearing.

01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:58.000
The sequence of testimony, of course, of course, the most effective part of that hearing was Fannie Lou Hamer's testimony".

01:56:58.000 --> 01:57:04.000
He argued and obtained the large ballroom.

01:57:04.000 --> 01:57:13.000
The administration intended they were going to be a small room with maybe television coverage.

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:19.000
And he was able to get that out of the administration.

01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:29.000
He held out through Sunday when he thought he had the votes. He claimed he had the votes to a Ferman already report.

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:34.000
So he was able to cause the delay.

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:44.000
He definitely had two roles. He was not 100% for the Freedom Democrats.

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:53.000
The other part of him was for himself and his role within the Democratic Party.

01:57:53.000 --> 01:58:07.000
What I found astounding was that he offered to withdraw in a letter to the White House.

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:17.000
But he said, but I advise that I not withdraw because then it would be run by the commies.

01:58:17.000 --> 01:58:24.000
I mean Bill Kunstler and Arthur Kinoy would become counsel for the Freedom Democrats at the convention.

01:58:24.000 --> 01:58:29.000
And he could keep things under control.

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:32.000
So this is a letter before the convention starts.

01:58:32.000 --> 01:58:44.000
Yes. And so at that point he clearly understands that where the challenge could end up going could be at conflict with his alliance with the National Democratic Party.

01:58:44.000 --> 01:58:51.000
The National Democratic Party did not want the main thing. They did not want a floor fight.

01:58:51.000 --> 01:59:00.000
A floor vote by all the delegates because that would highlight the totally different wings of the Democratic Party.

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:10.000
The North for civil rights, the South for segregation.

01:59:10.000 --> 01:59:24.000
Do you think when he became initially involved that he understood that the challenge could create this difficulty for the National Democratic Party?

01:59:24.000 --> 01:59:28.000
Do you think it became something bigger than what he initially thought?

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:36.000
Yes. I mean that he wanted to change the party. He wanted the reform.

01:59:36.000 --> 01:59:46.000
And when the reform would take place and how it would take place and whether the Freedom Democrats would be seated, they had to have to make the change in the party.

01:59:46.000 --> 02:00:00.000
They had to have a vehicle. And the Freedom Democratic Party was a vehicle to make the challenge and to force the leadership of the party to do something.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:22.000
Walter Reuther was never enthusiastic about the challenge. And he was close to Johnson and he saw a political problem that Rao did not see in a sense at the beginning.

02:00:22.000 --> 02:00:30.000
Are there other aspects of the challenge that has been particularly interesting for you to learn about through your research?

02:00:30.000 --> 02:00:45.000
Courtland Cox has been very open about the requests that Rep. Charles Diggs Jr, who was a member of the Credentials Committee,

02:00:45.000 --> 02:00:55.000
prominent liberal Democratic Congressman from Michigan.

02:00:55.000 --> 02:01:07.000
Diggs requested the list of members of the Credentials Committee who supported the MFDP.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:19.000
And he made that request to Bob Moses in Courland Cox. And Moses was reluctant. And Cox said, what do you mean? Do you think he's, of course.

02:01:19.000 --> 02:01:28.000
You know, we want to show our support. Diggs can then show the Chairman Chairman (David) Lawrence of the Credentials Committee our support.

02:01:28.000 --> 02:01:46.000
And there were, I think they say, 15 people on the list. And that list was handed over. I'm not sure whether it was Sunday night or Monday night.

02:01:46.000 --> 02:02:00.000
But overnight calls were made to all the people on the list. And they were threatened with some loss of privilege or something.

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:10.000
If they didn't change their vote, support the administration instead of the MFDP.

02:02:10.000 --> 02:02:23.000
The list is not very significant. The most you can say is what Michael Thelwell said to me is the names kept changing.

02:02:23.000 --> 02:02:46.000
Two weeks before the convention. Lawrence O'Brien, I think I've got that. Anyway, Johnson Aids were researching everybody on that, on the Credentials Committee.

02:02:46.000 --> 02:03:05.000
They knew exactly who the supporters were. Two from Michigan, Oregon, the two from New York. The man was okay. But they were worried about the woman.

02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:22.000
The woman from California. They pegged them exactly. And they pegged whether they were, whether they were, whether they were strong or weak. And what they, what they could do, they had the analysis well in hand.

02:03:22.000 --> 02:03:33.000
And they knew exactly how to reach the last two people. And they did. And then I found the evidence of how they, how they did it when they did it.

02:03:33.000 --> 02:03:38.000
What's the evidence? What's the documentation you found?

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:56.000
LBJ called the governor of Iowa. LBJ called the reporter, Hoit, I think his name is from Colorado, about the two Colorado delegates.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:15.000
They, they, they couldn't, the, the woman from New York was a secretary to mayor Wagner. And John English, the other delegate was supposed to, there was last minute trying to reach, reach her.

02:04:15.000 --> 02:04:31.000
The black woman from Maryland risk got, I'm not, this is, that's this is a secondary source, but got pressure from both in Maryland and from the national people.

02:04:31.000 --> 02:04:48.000
So, you said you thought of a few things this morning or the, when you were asking about what I learned about the convention challenge from research.

02:04:48.000 --> 02:05:11.000
And what I, what I tried to do was set it set up set up my proposed book to tell the story day by day, because so many writers confuse what happened. And then that really changes the way the freedom Democrats look, the way the delegates look.

02:05:11.000 --> 02:05:28.000
And I'm trying to give them more credit that they deserve. A lot of the emphasis is on Hubert Humphrey and that, that he worked out a compromise. And he did that because he wanted to become vice president.

02:05:28.000 --> 02:05:43.000
And Johnson put him up to do this, even though he was a friend of the civil rights movement. And that's, that's true in many ways, but Hubert Humphrey only acted on Monday. And he didn't succeed.

02:05:43.000 --> 02:05:59.000
What he did also on Monday was he had his staff people running around all the state delegations to make sure the state delegations would no longer support getting a roll call vote that they would go with the Johnson administration.

02:05:59.000 --> 02:06:10.000
Telling the state delegations, look, you're a friend of Humphrey, you want Humphrey to be vice president in order for him to get the nomination. We have to please Johnson. And this is what Johnson wants.

02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:28.000
So Humphrey was not totally unsuccessful on Monday. But it all happened because of Walter Reuther, who arrived on Tuesday in the middle of the night. And he worked with the Mondale subcommittee of the Credentials Committee to come up with the president.

02:06:28.000 --> 02:06:43.000
And he did the final, what Bob Moses calls symbolic Cross-corpus with Guyot #76.P3.13 offer that the delegates would be at large and that they would be individually named people.

02:06:44.000 --> 02:07:08.000
It was Ruther's manipulation and plan on Tuesday that made what Johnson wanted work. And it wasn't because Humphrey wasn't getting it done. And Ruther had to, the good negotiator and Humphrey says that we called him in because we needed him to.

02:07:09.000 --> 02:07:24.000
So when Humphrey wasn't able to make it work on Monday through actually sitting down and talking to people, then he calls in Ruther for a whole other level of arm twisting and deception manipulation.

02:07:24.000 --> 02:07:38.000
So holding two meetings simultaneously so that the credentials committee would vote and decide while the key people or the leadership is listening to what the offer is and refusing to accept it.

02:07:38.000 --> 02:07:53.000
But Humphrey did not have the power to negotiate. And Ruther decided not to negotiate. The war no negotiations. It was, somebody has said it was dictation. It was take it or leave it.

02:07:53.000 --> 02:08:10.000
And was it Ruther, so and it was a very conscious manipulation that Ruther sets up to essentially keep the leadership tied up while the credentials committee is voting.

02:08:10.000 --> 02:08:22.000
And did anybody besides Rao at the credentials committee meeting know that the leadership is in this meeting ostensibly discussing what the compromise might look like?

02:08:22.000 --> 02:08:40.000
The statements made at the credentials committee meeting were that Aaron Henry and Rev. Rev. Ed King knew about the offer and it was and accepted it. And Mondale didn't contradict that and Rao didn't contradict that.

02:08:40.000 --> 02:08:49.000
And what have Rev. Rev. Ed King and Aaron Henry said on the record about that? Nothing.

02:08:49.000 --> 02:08:55.000
I mean that's I think that's a new a new fact newly uncovered fact.

02:08:55.000 --> 02:09:08.000
That hasn't been emphasized much. And so they were so king and Henry are at that meeting with the leadership Bob Moses is at that meeting. Who else is at that meeting?

02:09:08.000 --> 02:09:18.000
Martin Luther King — Bayard Rustin was conducting the meeting. Not Hubert Humphrey not Walter Reuther.

02:09:18.000 --> 02:09:23.000
Were they there? King I guess Andrew Young.

02:09:23.000 --> 02:09:32.000
So were (Bayard) Rustin and (Walter) Reuther — were they there? — they were there but yes conducting it. Yes. Yes. Yeah. Yeah. They were there. Yes.

02:09:32.000 --> 02:09:46.000
So John said that you found something that Lyndon Johnson's press conference was already established before Fannie Lou Hamer's testimony" was already scheduled before Fannie Lou Hamer's testimony" testimony.

02:09:46.000 --> 02:10:06.000
The day the day before the Johnson told the press that he would be having a press conference in the middle of the afternoon and it would be full full press conference with camera.

02:10:06.000 --> 02:10:21.000
And the press is saying how come just because the governors are here for a meeting. Are you going to talk about the convention? Are you going to talk about your vice presidential nominee?

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:28.000
And he you know no answer but that but it was mysterious. And so he was ready.

02:10:28.000 --> 02:10:39.000
When he was watching the credentials committee testimony he was ready to cut it off. So basically he had anticipated that he might need to do something to distract people.

02:10:39.000 --> 02:10:50.000
I believe that that's the way we have to characterize it that he certainly knew that the committee hearing was scheduled.

02:10:50.000 --> 02:11:02.000
But everybody has written about it because of what Joseph L. Rauh Jr said. Joseph L. Rauh Jr told Anne Romaine that Johnson suddenly called the press conference.

02:11:02.000 --> 02:11:17.000
So everybody says hastily called hurriedly called. So they just take it right from Joseph L. Rauh Jr? Yes. Yes. Because gospel. Yeah. That's that's my that's my take. Nothing like a little research. It's great. Great fun.

02:11:17.000 --> 02:11:29.000
It must be interesting to do the research and match it up with your memories and then things like thinking you are at the state can stay convention and finding out you weren't.

02:11:29.000 --> 02:11:39.000
I mean that must be an interesting experience. A little test of how memory works. The same same thing happened to me with respect to orientation.

02:11:39.000 --> 02:11:47.000
People asked me what what happened at orientation and I've had trouble remembering that. So I've I've read about that too.

02:11:47.000 --> 02:11:56.000
So go back the difference between what you remember and what you know from what people have said about it. And I try to acknowledge that in my writing.

02:11:56.000 --> 02:12:05.000
So you you talked a little back. Was there anything else about the convention that you that you want to say at this point before we read the book?

02:12:11.000 --> 02:12:21.000
No, I don't think so. I need to focus in my own mind about what what are the newly new new facts and

02:12:22.000 --> 02:12:37.000
and what the main my main points are before I really start talking about the book. But what I what I've done is just try to lay lay it out in a in what I fear many people would find is pretty dull writing.

02:12:37.000 --> 02:12:50.000
But just day by day and then I interject what what I was doing and John DiPmer says that that that adds to the story that that makes it makes it more interesting.

02:12:50.000 --> 02:13:05.000
But I think by proceeding with my story of what I did organizing the MFDP and Greenville is and and how I got involved in the Mississippi summer project just makes you

02:13:05.000 --> 02:13:13.000
understand and makes the reader understand I hope you know kind of why I care why why this is important to me.

02:13:13.000 --> 02:13:22.000
And it's and I want to set the record straight you know that that it's it's so annoying to read historians mistakes.

02:13:22.000 --> 02:13:29.000
Yes, I understand. I agree whether they're my own or someone else's.

02:13:30.000 --> 02:13:38.000
Yeah, that's what Charles E. Cobb Jr said we all make mistakes. Charlie's very generous.

02:13:38.000 --> 02:13:50.000
But you said that when you came home and and ran into your mother or you know your father and your mother was upset at the idea that you might stay and that helped you make the decision to go to law school.

02:13:50.000 --> 02:13:57.000
What was it like to leave Mississippi or the convention challenge and then start law school immediately in the whole of that?

02:13:57.000 --> 02:14:13.000
Well, it wasn't immediate. I probably had you know the three weeks three weeks at home to you know get packed and get oriented to go one thing we did during that time was we had a fundraiser at the Central Presbyterian Church in summer.

02:14:13.000 --> 02:14:36.000
Mr. Schwerner and chips our wine who was a neighbor who was a volunteer in drew Mississippi I think and I spoke to a crowd of 600 people I think who wanted to hear hear about the Mississippi summer project.

02:14:36.000 --> 02:14:54.000
Even though it's a very republican town but there was so much press coverage during during the summer they were interested in the minister there had sent me a contribution earlier in the summer I know because I had a couple of articles in the local local newspaper.

02:14:54.000 --> 02:15:13.000
And we we we raised I asked and they agreed that that money would go for to support the Herbert Lee Memorial Freedom Center which was another project that I got involved with in Greenville at the end of the summer.

02:15:13.000 --> 02:15:31.000
We relied on all these established leaders that I was calling Uncle Tom's to now support organized fund a new community center that would be available to continue the cofo programs after the summer.

02:15:31.000 --> 02:15:45.000
And I went to a couple of meetings and we got the help of a couple volunteer lawyers and because Delta Ministry was coming in they they were able to make a contribution.

02:15:45.000 --> 02:15:58.000
And Dr. Matthew Page became the president and he was one of the important people for us during the summer.

02:15:58.000 --> 02:16:16.000
I hoped that he would be one of our new leaders. He was a young doctor just pretty much just starting his practice in Greenville local local man grew up in Greenville.

02:16:16.000 --> 02:16:45.000
And he I found out later became the president of Herbert Lee Memorial Community Center which was established not a new building as we planned with a volunteer lawyer but they purchased no they rented or whatever they acquired somehow a church and adapted it renovated it.

02:16:45.000 --> 02:17:14.000
For meetings and that became a head sort center and then was no longer in use but the the vice president of that new Herbert Lee organization was Charles Moore who had become active with us and he became a member of the city council for many many years and I did not have a chance to talk to him before he does.

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:19.000
I love before he died but I talked to his widow.

02:17:19.000 --> 02:17:31.000
Now you made a comment at the beginning of that talking about the traditional leadership and so I didn't understand so what was what was their role in this.

02:17:31.000 --> 02:17:42.000
They we we organized them to raise the money to build a community center.

02:17:42.000 --> 02:17:48.000
I see and you basically targeted them because they had the means yes yes yes.

02:17:48.000 --> 02:18:00.000
And where did the idea for the community center come from us okay the cofo whatever the summer project we saw the need that they had one a one-room building that they were using.

02:18:00.000 --> 02:18:12.000
And they they wanted a new new facility and so the money that was just in a side because that's what I the only thing I did when I got back home was related to that.

02:18:12.000 --> 02:18:17.000
I drove across the country to Stanford to law school.

02:18:17.000 --> 02:18:29.000
I lived on campus in a brand new apartment building for graduate housing with Karen Davis who is the president of the state.

02:18:29.000 --> 02:18:43.000
Who's younger sister is Linda Davis who's a volunteer in ruralville Freedom School teacher who was at Oberlin College and had decided to stay for a year.

02:18:43.000 --> 02:18:58.000
So this was a wonderful connection and Karen's younger second younger sister was a freshman at Stanford and she's now I think I think she's now a judge in San Francisco.

02:18:58.000 --> 02:19:10.000
But that that was a nice nice to be able to continue the connection through through the Davises but it was that coincidence or did you make the coincidence to coincidence.

02:19:10.000 --> 02:19:17.000
I believe it was coincidences. Karen was a second year law student.

02:19:17.000 --> 02:19:33.000
the Law Students Civil Rights Research Council I got involved with that on campus we we had meetings we had a small group we raised tried to raise money there was a dean that was supportive.

02:19:33.000 --> 02:19:45.000
I found in my papers that I went to Berkeley once for some kind of an event in that Arthur Kinoy there.

02:19:45.000 --> 02:20:14.000
But then I wanted to go back to Mississippi as a law clerk and so I applied and I was selected and assigned to the Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under Law and about exam time I was invited by James Danner to his office to talk about Mississippi because he and one of his partners were going down.

02:20:14.000 --> 02:20:41.000
For a month I think or two weeks or three weeks soon with the lawyers committee and I didn't know I mean I this was a Friday afternoon I was relaxed and I couldn't believe the naivete of these men as I was trying to describe my experiences in Mississippi.

02:20:41.000 --> 02:20:56.000
And soon I learned from Bill Robinson with the law students civil rights research council in New York that I would be reassigned.

02:20:56.000 --> 02:21:11.000
They were they were building an office on Ferris Street with a with a double paying glass window spending it was a problem spending $4,000 or something which I thought was extremely extravagant.

02:21:11.000 --> 02:21:27.000
So they decided that they didn't want a movement person or they wanted one less less law clerk.

02:21:27.000 --> 02:21:56.000
I learned later that I don't know how I learned this whether Bill told me Bill must have told me when I saw him later in New York that I was they thought I was childish and immature because you didn't defer to them because I was just sounding off about you know I was I was sounding rather militant you know I mean I was I I disassociated myself from the movement.

02:21:57.000 --> 02:22:09.000
There's no question about that during law school I was very afraid of flunking out of law school my older brother had just flunked out of University of Minnesota law school.

02:22:09.000 --> 02:22:16.000
And I was not confident we didn't get any grades very competitive environment.

02:22:16.000 --> 02:22:34.000
And I was I was getting mailings I think I was still getting the the newsletters southern patriot the snake student voice student voice from that I was getting my senior year in college.

02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:45.000
And I was reading the San Francisco Chronicle that's all it was reading I really didn't know what was going on in Mississippi anymore I was studying.

02:22:45.000 --> 02:23:00.000
But I but it all came back in this conversation with these lawyers was it was it was hard to be cut off like that or did you just make the was it hard to be cut off or did you just know transition no it was a natural transition yeah.

02:23:00.000 --> 02:23:21.000
So so I built all me that that to go to Jackson and go somewhere I don't know where I was supposed to go but he would find another assignment so I was assigned to the National Lawyer's Guild and I lived in two glue with Claudia Shropshire Morcom who was there for one year.

02:23:21.000 --> 02:23:45.000
And we were she was the National Lawyers Guild was that summer of 1965 coordinating groups of volunteer lawyers who came to Mississippi to evaluate the need for litigation to open title three public facilities.

02:23:45.000 --> 02:24:08.000
Library swimming pools not restaurants not not public accommodations but public facilities county by county so I was the law clerk to help these volunteer lawyers and traveled traveled out to the counties that were selected to do that you remember which counties.

02:24:08.000 --> 02:24:28.000
Madison Madison County Madison we went to Greenwood we went to Greenville that's where I saw Mrs. Britton and you were dressed and Jackson was was one.

02:24:29.000 --> 02:24:48.000
But I I lost my fury I mean I there I was doing legal work I mean I was really in becoming a lawyer in transition to law did you have any concerns about working with the National Lawyer's Guild that was I think why I mentioned that about my father.

02:24:48.000 --> 02:25:17.000
Yes although you know we certainly heard the lecture at orientation from from Bob Moses that that red baiting was a thing of the past he was regardless of what the National Council of Churches said he was accepting legal services from anyone he was accepting help from anyone and he wasn't going to be influenced that that the movement was going to be tired with a label of the law.

02:25:18.000 --> 02:25:43.000
So I remember that during the summer that when we were called communists that that was just red baiting that was that was to be dismissed we were we weren't communist you know we weren't socialist we were the civil rights movement and it was straight forward honest and real.

02:25:43.000 --> 02:26:07.000
And I when I was assigned to the National Lawyers Guild whatever reservation I might have had you know later becoming a lawyer and all of that I was an employee directly of the Law Students Civil Rights Research Council I never I never joined the National Lawyers Guild as an attorney I joined in retirement.

02:26:08.000 --> 02:26:34.000
And at the beginning of May I was in Detroit and I saw Claudia more come and we had a wonderful wonderful reunion with John Hardy who she knows in her building we had a we had a long long luncheon but she told the story which I had no recollection of that one day I came out of the bathroom and I said I think there's a peeping Tom out there.

02:26:34.000 --> 02:27:03.000
And she yelled Lisa get the gun of course we had no gun and she she heard somebody scampering off but that was it was a good learning experience I had a good summer but going back to Greenville I didn't look anybody up I didn't inquire about the Herbert Lee Center.

02:27:03.000 --> 02:27:28.000
I didn't I wasn't curious about Delta Ministry. I was like what person I you know I mean I I had I I've people some there people who have read my my drafts and say what what is this how do you not know that there was a Herbert Lee community center until you read a book after you retired.

02:27:28.000 --> 02:27:43.000
But that's how far I think I disassociated myself from the from the movement after law school well my after my second year I clerked at the office of economic opportunity in Washington and the general counsel's office.

02:27:43.000 --> 02:28:03.000
I think my close friend Vicki Popkin was I think she was working in New York that that summer but she wanted to she had she had worked for two years before law school in between college and law school so she she was going to be working in Washington after we finished law school.

02:28:03.000 --> 02:28:17.000
And I wanted to I didn't want to work in New York didn't have any connection with Boston New York would have been too close to home while Washington was a natural place for me to work.

02:28:17.000 --> 02:28:46.000
That was a good summer and then third year looking for a position I applied for all the civil rights positions which were highly competitive very few of them at the Justice Department or whatever and the any poverty program was just beginning so I applied to be legal services attorney in California took the California bar and they wanted bar admission they wanted to put you in the courtroom immediately.

02:28:47.000 --> 02:29:14.000
And I wouldn't have the bar admission until January so I continued looking in Washington but I my first job was with the United Planning Organization which was the Community Action Agency receiving federal funds and a poverty money and we wrote a delegate agency contracts.

02:29:14.000 --> 02:29:26.000
Finally that federal money out to community groups and DC government it was a regional so even including the neighboring county governments.

02:29:26.000 --> 02:29:43.000
And in within two years I felt the effects of black power the atmosphere of the agency changed I felt less less welcome as a white trying to do my work.

02:29:43.000 --> 02:29:51.000
And I also felt that I could contribute more elsewhere or that I was not doing as much as I might.

02:29:51.000 --> 02:30:12.000
So I resigned interesting also that I was at the United Planning Organization the exact two years that Wiley A. Branton Sr was there as the executive director so I was preparing correspondence for his signature and he was I thought the world of him he's a wonderful wonderful man.

02:30:12.000 --> 02:30:41.000
I took the DC bar and applied to for private practice in DC and Trovon Bauer recognized that I knew something about contracts and hired me and I got into the field of government contracts and practiced in that field there and with Morgan, Lewis & Bockius for

02:30:41.000 --> 02:31:08.000
almost ten years I guess and that qualified me to apply to be an administrative judge on a board of contract appeals and after a three hour interview I was rated and I mean I was initially qualified under the statute for contract disputes act of 1978.

02:31:08.000 --> 02:31:25.000
I was then qualified highly rated highly qualified eligible for one of the few positions that there are as a board of contract appeals judge and found an opportunity at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.

02:31:25.000 --> 02:31:29.000
So what does that work in tail?

02:31:30.000 --> 02:31:57.000
We handled disputes that were presented by contractors once a contracting officer for a federal agency issues a final decision whether that's a terminating a contract for default or denying a claim for additional funds defective specifications change orders changes.

02:31:57.000 --> 02:32:21.000
The contractor can appeal either to the US Court of Federal claims or to an administrative board we were intended to provide fast and expensive informal relief but it tended to be quite quite litigious once once the attorneys were representing the contractors.

02:32:21.000 --> 02:32:50.000
We conducted full trial type proceedings discovery sworn witness testimony transcripts and briefs and then wrote detailed decisions of findings of fact and conclusions of law that were issued by a panel of three judges and subject to review and appeal only to the US Court.

02:32:51.000 --> 02:33:15.000
We did not have a large caseload that would sustain the required statutorily required board of three full time judges.

02:33:15.000 --> 02:33:26.000
We initiated the idea of a merger of the NASA Board of Contract Appeals with the Department of Defense Board and I became a judge on the NASA Board of Contract Appeals.

02:33:26.000 --> 02:33:32.000
So did that just change which contractors but not really the work with the work was the same.

02:33:32.000 --> 02:33:49.000
It was the same format absolutely but the caseload was huge the variety of appeals was huge and the jurisdiction was worldwide.

02:33:49.000 --> 02:34:01.000
So we traveled for our hearings for the convenience of the party so I had some interesting and some uninteresting trips.

02:34:01.000 --> 02:34:14.000
Did your experiences with the civil rights movement influence you in any of the subsequent legal work or your life.

02:34:14.000 --> 02:34:37.000
Somebody else asked me that recently and I think it's interesting that we talked about nonviolence and civil disobedience so much in the civil rights movement and yet in my work I was confined by federal law.

02:34:37.000 --> 02:34:43.000
I was my obligation was to apply the rule of law in the decision of cases.

02:34:43.000 --> 02:35:04.000
What I tried to do was to offer the contractor a full and fair hearing and to listen and to be fair and then to of course write a decision that would be understandable.

02:35:04.000 --> 02:35:12.000
Did you ever feel like you were constrained by what federal law was in terms of what you thought might be just or right.

02:35:12.000 --> 02:35:17.000
Yes. There were situations where the situation cried out.

02:35:17.000 --> 02:35:29.000
The poor contractor had really been victimized by the way the thing went and this was there.

02:35:29.000 --> 02:35:36.000
But in the end you needed to say no I'm sorry.

02:35:36.000 --> 02:35:42.000
Was that hard? It was something you had to do.

02:35:42.000 --> 02:35:51.000
So what made you decide you wanted to write, retire and write something more interesting?

02:35:51.000 --> 02:36:01.000
I enjoyed the job very much and I enjoyed the independence of the job and the way everything about it.

02:36:01.000 --> 02:36:10.000
But I learned how to do it. Every case was different and it was always interesting in that respect.

02:36:10.000 --> 02:36:19.000
But there was something of a formula to be applied to getting to a result.

02:36:19.000 --> 02:36:45.000
I got the idea for the book from a friend knowing I have a very large library of books that I acquired as they were published about the civil rights movement.

02:36:45.000 --> 02:36:54.000
When I mentioned the library she suggested that I write a book.

02:36:54.000 --> 02:36:59.000
The idea took.

02:36:59.000 --> 02:37:13.000
I really started before I retired and I talked to a literary agent and she asked for the first chapter.

02:37:13.000 --> 02:37:20.000
I wasn't prepared to stay up nights when I was working and write the first chapter.

02:37:20.000 --> 02:37:29.000
I was writing behind closed doors all those years.

02:37:29.000 --> 02:37:39.000
It would not be as interesting as rethinking and revisiting Mississippi Freedom.

02:37:39.000 --> 02:37:45.000
I knew the Mississippi Summer Project and the Mississippi Civil Rights Movement.

02:37:45.000 --> 02:37:54.000
It just opened up so much for me because I have gone to the conferences of the Veterans of the Mississippi Civil Rights Movement in Jackson.

02:37:54.000 --> 02:38:02.000
It just met so many new people. It is a whole new world for me.

02:38:02.000 --> 02:38:11.000
I think it really did have a huge impact on me.

02:38:11.000 --> 02:38:28.000
Even though I went dormant for the years after leaving law school, I did not get involved in the women's movement or the peace movement.

02:38:28.000 --> 02:38:37.000
I was focused on my career.

02:38:37.000 --> 02:38:45.000
I found the writing much more difficult than I expected.

02:38:45.000 --> 02:38:49.000
The project, the amount of time it takes.

02:38:49.000 --> 02:38:56.000
I have been warned about it. Mary King has been very helpful to me.

02:38:56.000 --> 02:39:03.000
Mentoring me and she has extremely high standards.

02:39:03.000 --> 02:39:14.000
She is very meticulous in her writing and she read a couple of pages that I had written at some point and I couldn't believe what she turned them into and the questions that she asked.

02:39:14.000 --> 02:39:20.000
I hadn't expected it all when I went over to her house for tea.

02:39:20.000 --> 02:39:25.000
You didn't know that you were going to have a critique session?

02:39:25.000 --> 02:39:29.000
Pure review right here.

02:39:29.000 --> 02:39:32.000
One of those ones where she has more to say about your writing.

02:39:32.000 --> 02:39:38.000
Two pages come back for everyone you send in.

02:39:38.000 --> 02:39:47.000
Did your perspective on your experience and what you did? Has that changed as you look back on it?

02:39:47.000 --> 02:39:54.000
I'm interested in what other people say to me.

02:39:54.000 --> 02:40:00.000
They can't believe that I did that or that I took such courage.

02:40:00.000 --> 02:40:07.000
I never felt that way.

02:40:07.000 --> 02:40:16.000
I'm trying to follow what other people are doing and writing about and saying.

02:40:16.000 --> 02:40:19.000
As students we changed history.

02:40:19.000 --> 02:40:24.000
I recently heard.

02:40:24.000 --> 02:40:32.000
We certainly did because we did not influence the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

02:40:32.000 --> 02:40:37.000
That's a mistake that some people make. Freedom Summer did not have anything to do with that.

02:40:37.000 --> 02:40:41.000
It was done before we got there.

02:40:41.000 --> 02:40:44.000
But the Voting Rights Act certainly.

02:40:44.000 --> 02:40:47.000
The reform is a democratic party.

02:40:47.000 --> 02:40:50.000
It's just absolutely incredible.

02:40:50.000 --> 02:40:59.000
The possibility of the election of Obama in 2008 is directly traced to the work that we did.

02:40:59.000 --> 02:41:04.000
The work was not done by a few leaders.

02:41:04.000 --> 02:41:08.000
The work was done by many, many, many people.

02:41:08.000 --> 02:41:20.000
Maybe the SNCC activists, the students who really were in there at a very, very dangerous time to themselves personally.

02:41:20.000 --> 02:41:23.000
Maybe the volunteers going in there.

02:41:23.000 --> 02:41:25.000
By the way, there were only 500 of us.

02:41:25.000 --> 02:41:29.000
There were not 1,000 college-age volunteers.

02:41:29.000 --> 02:41:33.000
There were just a lot of professionals that dipped in for a couple of weeks.

02:41:33.000 --> 02:41:37.000
They make up the 1,000.

02:41:37.000 --> 02:41:40.000
We made a difference.

02:41:40.000 --> 02:41:45.000
If we made a difference, maybe it took a long time, but we made a difference.

02:41:45.000 --> 02:41:47.000
We made a contribution.

02:41:47.000 --> 02:41:53.000
Things are better than I want young people today to believe that.

02:41:53.000 --> 02:42:00.000
Not to be cynical and pessimistic about our dysfunctional, currently dysfunctional government.

02:42:00.000 --> 02:42:04.000
With a Congress that can't seem to pass any legislation.

02:42:04.000 --> 02:42:14.000
But there is a way, one of the things that I learned to do, I think, in North Carolina, was to write a letter to state a position.

02:42:14.000 --> 02:42:16.000
I did that during the summer.

02:42:16.000 --> 02:42:27.000
I have done that since, but I think I've done it more complaining about a product than on a political issue.

02:42:27.000 --> 02:42:36.000
Living in DC, we don't have a congressman and congressperson and senators.

02:42:36.000 --> 02:42:40.000
But someday we may, but I think that's a deterrent.

02:42:40.000 --> 02:42:42.000
But I've always voted.

02:42:42.000 --> 02:42:48.000
The registrar in North Carolina said, make sure you always vote.

02:42:48.000 --> 02:42:50.000
We've got to participate.

02:42:50.000 --> 02:42:56.000
And it's up to every individual to do that.

02:42:56.000 --> 02:43:08.000
And once a single person finds a passion, finds something that's important, something that they want to change, then it's time to find somebody else who feels the same way.

02:43:08.000 --> 02:43:14.000
And to reach out and once you have a larger group, maybe that's what we call community organizing.

02:43:14.000 --> 02:43:19.000
But getting together into a larger mass, it will make a difference.

02:43:19.000 --> 02:43:26.000
And I feel it's important to encourage that among young people.

02:43:26.000 --> 02:43:30.000
I have not done public speaking.

02:43:30.000 --> 02:43:39.000
I have not spoken to student groups, but when I do have a chance to talk to a student, that's what I want to say.

02:43:39.000 --> 02:43:50.000
Yeah, I wondered when you were talking about that, because my experience is that sometimes that a lot of students do take that away from actually studying the Civil Rights Movement.

02:43:50.000 --> 02:43:54.000
It's one of the things that they can get if they're taught it in a certain way.

02:43:54.000 --> 02:44:00.000
And that they often find it really empowering to use that word.

02:44:00.000 --> 02:44:05.000
But to talk to people who were their age and did do things like this.

02:44:05.000 --> 02:44:08.000
And it makes them ask themselves questions, what is my...

02:44:08.000 --> 02:44:14.000
So I wondered if you had actually spent any time talking to students if you had that opportunity.

02:44:14.000 --> 02:44:23.000
I did speak to one history class at my high school.

02:44:23.000 --> 02:44:29.000
And that was over 10 years ago, I think.

02:44:29.000 --> 02:44:36.000
And somebody said, oh, they really lit up when you read from your diary.

02:44:36.000 --> 02:44:40.000
I can imagine.

02:44:40.000 --> 02:44:52.000
Well, can you think of anything else? Anything that we haven't covered and should?

02:44:52.000 --> 02:44:56.000
I don't think you asked me if I was scared.

02:44:56.000 --> 02:44:59.000
Were you scared?

02:44:59.000 --> 02:45:02.000
I was scared at the beginning.

02:45:02.000 --> 02:45:10.000
But I wasn't scared when I left Oxford, which so many summer volunteers were.

02:45:10.000 --> 02:45:15.000
Particularly, of course, the second group.

02:45:15.000 --> 02:45:20.000
But sitting in the Freedom House and hearing the cars going around.

02:45:20.000 --> 02:45:26.000
And not knowing. It was the uncertainty.

02:45:26.000 --> 02:45:29.000
And then we learned that, oh, that was the police.

02:45:29.000 --> 02:45:32.000
They were making sure that nothing was going to happen to us.

02:45:32.000 --> 02:45:35.000
And you wonder if that's true, but I think it was.

02:45:35.000 --> 02:45:38.000
Because that was the nature of Greenville.

02:45:38.000 --> 02:45:41.000
That they wanted to make sure that nothing happened.

02:45:41.000 --> 02:45:48.000
There was no clan there. There was no citizens council was allowed to organize in Greenville.

02:45:48.000 --> 02:45:51.000
Yeah, Greenville was a little bit unusual.

02:45:51.000 --> 02:45:54.000
Right.

02:45:54.000 --> 02:45:59.000
I mean, it was probably considered the safest or one of the safest places in the state, right?

02:45:59.000 --> 02:46:02.000
Right.

02:46:02.000 --> 02:46:03.000
Yeah.

02:46:03.000 --> 02:46:06.000
Do you think that had something to do with you're not being afraid because you knew where you were going?

02:46:06.000 --> 02:46:12.000
Or was it you just became confident through the orientation?

02:46:12.000 --> 02:46:15.000
No, I was reassured by Greenville.

02:46:15.000 --> 02:46:20.000
You know, that being assigned there.

02:46:20.000 --> 02:46:29.000
And the only time that I was concerned as so many people always have written about,

02:46:29.000 --> 02:46:35.000
when you're in a car and you're on a highway, particularly at night,

02:46:35.000 --> 02:46:38.000
you notice the pickup trucks.

02:46:38.000 --> 02:46:42.000
And you notice the rifle racks in the back of the pickup trucks.

02:46:42.000 --> 02:46:48.000
And they're following you and you just worry, you know.

02:46:48.000 --> 02:46:51.000
That was a standard concern.

02:46:51.000 --> 02:47:00.000
The closest thing I came to violence was being at a VFW dance at the beginning of the summer.

02:47:00.000 --> 02:47:03.000
You know, in this huge open hall.

02:47:03.000 --> 02:47:05.000
And of course, I was one of...

02:47:05.000 --> 02:47:08.000
I might have been the only white woman there.

02:47:08.000 --> 02:47:10.000
I don't know whether any of my...

02:47:10.000 --> 02:47:16.000
The group of volunteers went to this dance because it was a fundraiser sponsored by Charles Moore,

02:47:16.000 --> 02:47:19.000
who was very active in that VFW,

02:47:19.000 --> 02:47:22.000
to raise money for the project.

02:47:22.000 --> 02:47:25.000
And I said, well, if they're raising money for our project, we should go.

02:47:25.000 --> 02:47:32.000
And I wanted to talk about voter registration with all these black dudes there, right, at the dance.

02:47:32.000 --> 02:47:35.000
And so I was dancing.

02:47:35.000 --> 02:47:39.000
I don't know whether I probably had a cup of beer.

02:47:39.000 --> 02:47:43.000
And dance with one guy.

02:47:43.000 --> 02:47:45.000
Dance with a second guy.

02:47:45.000 --> 02:47:48.000
The second guy asked me to go out on the porch, which was a great relief,

02:47:48.000 --> 02:47:52.000
because it's so hot and crowded on the dance floor.

02:47:52.000 --> 02:47:55.000
The first guy comes out and pulls a knife.

02:47:55.000 --> 02:48:02.000
Danger at the VFW.

02:48:02.000 --> 02:48:06.000
That also ended my interest in black men for the summer.

02:48:06.000 --> 02:48:08.000
You know, I wasn't going to get involved.

02:48:08.000 --> 02:48:12.000
I didn't need to date the summer in 1964.

02:48:12.000 --> 02:48:18.000
So I went across the street and sat down at a picnic table at some kind of a barbecue joint

02:48:18.000 --> 02:48:26.000
and waited for my colleagues to take me back to the safe black community.

02:48:26.000 --> 02:48:29.000
Some of the colleagues, other colleagues who were at the dance,

02:48:29.000 --> 02:48:33.000
we just had one carload, I think.

